WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.860 --> 00:00:03.510
Good morning, everyone. I'm Sarah Tajjan from the Children's Hospital of

2
00:00:03.560 --> 00:00:07.520
Philadelphia. I'm delighted to welcome you to this very far, far room away

3
00:00:07.580 --> 00:00:11.560
in Room 28 for a wonderful education session today

4
00:00:11.680 --> 00:00:15.340
on small patients and big problems, precision medicine

5
00:00:15.380 --> 00:00:17.680
approaches for childhood cancers.

6
00:00:17.940 --> 00:00:19.620
I'm joined today by my good colleagues, Dr.

7
00:00:19.700 --> 00:00:23.140
David Ziegler from Sydney Children's Hospital and Cancer Institute, and Dr.

8
00:00:23.580 --> 00:00:24.320
Catherine Janeway

9
00:00:25.140 --> 00:00:27.720
from Boston Children's and Dana-Farber Cancer Institute.

10
00:00:28.420 --> 00:00:32.080
We will be providing three talks today for you on precision

11
00:00:32.140 --> 00:00:35.010
medicine in childhood CNS tumors, bone sarcomas, and

12
00:00:35.040 --> 00:00:38.910
leukemias. Each talk will be about 20 minutes, and then we'll have about

13
00:00:38.960 --> 00:00:41.000
10 minutes for questions after each speaker.

14
00:00:41.680 --> 00:00:44.800
I will ask you all in the audience, number one, we're a little bit lonely up here,

15
00:00:44.880 --> 00:00:47.200
so please feel free to move forward so you can hear and see better.

16
00:00:47.960 --> 00:00:51.460
But if you have a question, please go up to the microphone afterwards because we

17
00:00:51.520 --> 00:00:55.150
have a robust online presence. And please give us your name and where you're from

18
00:00:55.320 --> 00:00:59.140
before you ask your question. And with that, I will introduce Dr. David Ziegler.

19
00:00:59.320 --> 00:00:59.800
Thanks so much.

20
00:01:08.460 --> 00:01:09.140
Okay.

21
00:01:15.220 --> 00:01:19.210
Okay, so thank you so much to the organizers for inviting me to speak and

22
00:01:19.300 --> 00:01:19.880
for everyone

23
00:01:20.860 --> 00:01:24.420
here who managed to find their way to the very last room in the

24
00:01:24.460 --> 00:01:25.300
convention center,

25
00:01:26.260 --> 00:01:30.120
where they've hidden the best talks, I think, the best topic, at least,

26
00:01:30.280 --> 00:01:33.840
on pediatric cancer. So I'll be talking about

27
00:01:34.080 --> 00:01:37.420
precision medicine in childhood CNS tumors and

28
00:01:37.800 --> 00:01:41.680
beyond, just to give me a bit more scope to go a little bit beyond CNS tumors

29
00:01:41.740 --> 00:01:45.640
as well. And I wanted to start just with a few basic concepts about

30
00:01:45.660 --> 00:01:49.160
precision medicine, particular, I think, bugbears of mine.

31
00:01:50.320 --> 00:01:54.300
I'll focus on some of our results from Australia and our precision

32
00:01:54.360 --> 00:01:57.740
medicine program and the Zero program and really talk about the

33
00:01:57.780 --> 00:01:59.220
application of

34
00:02:00.060 --> 00:02:00.520
global

35
00:02:01.380 --> 00:02:05.220
precision medicine programs for CNS tumors, both high-risk

36
00:02:05.280 --> 00:02:08.340
tumors, which has been the main focus, but also

37
00:02:09.160 --> 00:02:12.320
non-high-risk tumors, which I think is also particularly interesting.

38
00:02:13.640 --> 00:02:17.340
So starting off with a very simple question of what is precision

39
00:02:17.400 --> 00:02:21.260
medicine, and I think when we think about it, we think about really the first image

40
00:02:21.320 --> 00:02:24.940
there, the magic bullet. Finding that genetic change in a tumor,

41
00:02:25.340 --> 00:02:29.100
finding the drug that targets that genetic change, and really

42
00:02:29.160 --> 00:02:32.840
finding that magic bullet that will wipe away the tumor for that patient.

43
00:02:33.380 --> 00:02:37.300
But really, I think that's a small number of patients

44
00:02:37.380 --> 00:02:39.420
that that paradigm actually fits.

45
00:02:39.500 --> 00:02:42.470
And more often, precision medicine really can be about

46
00:02:42.500 --> 00:02:46.410
fine-tuning the treatment for different patients using

47
00:02:46.420 --> 00:02:50.109
that genomic information that we can gather through whatever testing we're

48
00:02:50.160 --> 00:02:54.130
doing to adjust the treatments that we're giving,

49
00:02:54.150 --> 00:02:58.100
understand better prognosis for that patient, or work out

50
00:02:58.140 --> 00:02:59.980
different ways to modulate their treatment.

51
00:03:00.520 --> 00:03:01.700
And also increasingly,

52
00:03:02.520 --> 00:03:04.660
really about using it as a diagnostic tool.

53
00:03:04.800 --> 00:03:08.260
So not necessarily about finding the magic bullet, but about using the

54
00:03:08.280 --> 00:03:11.640
genomics to understand what is the tumor that we're actually treating,

55
00:03:12.040 --> 00:03:15.230
rather than just looking down the microscope like we've been doing for hundreds of

56
00:03:15.280 --> 00:03:18.920
years, looking at the tumor and making the diagnosis based on the genetic

57
00:03:19.000 --> 00:03:20.260
profile of that tumor.

58
00:03:22.500 --> 00:03:25.420
So that's precision medicine, but what is targeted therapy?

59
00:03:25.480 --> 00:03:29.240
And again, I think, we think about this, and we've got that general

60
00:03:29.300 --> 00:03:31.420
concept like I introduced of the magic bullet.

61
00:03:31.440 --> 00:03:34.920
But when we think, "Well, here's a targeted therapy.

62
00:03:35.000 --> 00:03:37.180
We've got a pathway. We've got targets.

63
00:03:37.220 --> 00:03:41.000
We give a drug that specifically attacks those targets." However, in this

64
00:03:41.100 --> 00:03:44.280
case, the drug is CP, which is actually cisplatin.

65
00:03:44.900 --> 00:03:48.760
So I think every drug that we use is in some way a

66
00:03:48.860 --> 00:03:52.420
targeted therapy. Every chemotherapy essentially has a target.

67
00:03:53.280 --> 00:03:57.140
And even those drugs here that we think of as more targeted

68
00:03:57.180 --> 00:03:59.739
therapies, less generally cytotoxic, when you look at...

69
00:03:59.780 --> 00:04:03.340
And these are just some of the tyrosine kinase inhibitors, actually have

70
00:04:03.380 --> 00:04:04.780
multiple different targets.

71
00:04:07.340 --> 00:04:10.980
We like to think we know what the targets are and what we're targeting, but often

72
00:04:11.520 --> 00:04:14.880
the drug may actually be doing different things or hitting other targets, both ones

73
00:04:14.920 --> 00:04:17.459
we know about, but are also ones that we don't know about.

74
00:04:18.880 --> 00:04:22.520
And then, of course, we have drugs where we do really know what the

75
00:04:22.580 --> 00:04:25.760
target is, and CDK4/6 inhibitors is a very good

76
00:04:25.780 --> 00:04:29.250
example. But those pathways may be so complex that

77
00:04:29.320 --> 00:04:32.980
actually while we know what the drug's hitting, we don't really know what the

78
00:04:33.000 --> 00:04:36.920
biomarker is. And I think CDK4/6 inhibitors is a really good example

79
00:04:36.980 --> 00:04:39.440
where they're used as a standard

80
00:04:40.460 --> 00:04:43.980
tool in adult breast cancer. But in pediatric cancers

81
00:04:44.620 --> 00:04:48.270
and indeed many other cancers, we still really don't know what the biomarker is

82
00:04:48.300 --> 00:04:51.590
that we should be targeting or which genomic

83
00:04:52.220 --> 00:04:55.520
signals or pathways are the ones that tell us this is the right

84
00:04:56.380 --> 00:04:59.360
tumor for which we should be trying these different inhibitors.

85
00:05:01.460 --> 00:05:05.220
So this is the simple paradigm that we think about with precision

86
00:05:05.240 --> 00:05:06.510
medicine and targeted therapies.

87
00:05:06.560 --> 00:05:10.100
We find the pathway, we find the gene that gives us the switch,

88
00:05:10.740 --> 00:05:12.200
and we switch it off, and we

89
00:05:13.220 --> 00:05:14.540
kill off the tumor.

90
00:05:15.820 --> 00:05:19.780
Again, the reality is most tumors that we're dealing with have pathways that look a

91
00:05:19.820 --> 00:05:23.660
little bit more like this. And yes, maybe there is one of those

92
00:05:23.700 --> 00:05:27.150
wires that if we find it, that's the real tumor driver, and if you switch it off,

93
00:05:27.260 --> 00:05:29.880
then you will switch off everything that drives it.

94
00:05:29.920 --> 00:05:33.660
But more often there may be wires and switches there that are

95
00:05:33.700 --> 00:05:37.600
doing nothing or maybe there's multiple pathways that will be

96
00:05:37.660 --> 00:05:41.400
activated, and we need to switch multiple of these drivers off.

97
00:05:41.440 --> 00:05:44.140
So these are all the things we need to think about.

98
00:05:44.380 --> 00:05:48.360
It's not just as simple as finding a genetic change and finding a drug,

99
00:05:48.460 --> 00:05:51.980
but it's really understanding how those different pathways and targets

100
00:05:52.400 --> 00:05:53.820
and everything work in those different

101
00:05:53.840 --> 00:05:57.726
tumors.So putting this

102
00:05:57.756 --> 00:06:01.676
together, there's multiple different programs around the world trying to

103
00:06:02.096 --> 00:06:06.086
get all this information and work out what we can do, how we can use it

104
00:06:06.116 --> 00:06:08.876
to enhance the outcomes for our patients.

105
00:06:09.286 --> 00:06:13.136
In Australia, our program's called the Zero Childhood

106
00:06:13.196 --> 00:06:17.096
Cancer Program, and many different

107
00:06:17.156 --> 00:06:18.156
programs use different

108
00:06:20.036 --> 00:06:23.536
genetic testing. Sometimes it's just a gene panel, sometimes it's whole

109
00:06:23.616 --> 00:06:27.536
exome. In Australia, we use a whole genome, RNA-Seq,

110
00:06:27.556 --> 00:06:31.336
DNA methylation profiling, and indeed, try and do drug screening and animal

111
00:06:31.376 --> 00:06:35.116
modeling as well and try and pull that all together initially for the

112
00:06:35.156 --> 00:06:39.076
highest-risk patients. And so the question is really how useful is this?

113
00:06:39.116 --> 00:06:40.736
It's something that we're all trying to do.

114
00:06:41.656 --> 00:06:42.756
In Australia,

115
00:06:43.676 --> 00:06:46.396
most of our patients or the largest group is

116
00:06:47.216 --> 00:06:50.656
high-risk brain tumors as well as then sarcomas and other

117
00:06:50.796 --> 00:06:54.776
cancers. So how useful is doing this for all this patient group?

118
00:06:57.516 --> 00:06:57.786
And

119
00:06:58.616 --> 00:07:02.596
when we started our program, this was actually one of the first patients who

120
00:07:02.656 --> 00:07:06.496
came through the program. It was a patient, a young infant who had a high-grade

121
00:07:06.656 --> 00:07:09.116
brain tumor initially thought to be an ependymoma.

122
00:07:09.836 --> 00:07:13.696
Later, the pathology and the sequencing helped us realize it

123
00:07:13.736 --> 00:07:14.276
was actually

124
00:07:15.816 --> 00:07:19.336
a high-grade glioma, and we found a TRK fusion.

125
00:07:19.396 --> 00:07:22.366
This was right at the time that larotrectinib had just been developed.

126
00:07:22.396 --> 00:07:26.366
It actually wasn't yet available in Australia, but we managed to get it

127
00:07:27.596 --> 00:07:30.536
flown in for this patient, and this was really the

128
00:07:30.836 --> 00:07:34.676
case that we're looking for where we're

129
00:07:34.716 --> 00:07:37.856
looking for that magic bullet. So this was a patient who had failed

130
00:07:38.116 --> 00:07:42.056
chemotherapy, radiation therapy, was in palliative care, had literally

131
00:07:42.116 --> 00:07:45.996
just been sent home to die. We were waiting for this drug to be flown

132
00:07:46.076 --> 00:07:49.936
in. This is really that paradigm

133
00:07:49.976 --> 00:07:52.916
of the highly targeted drug that really doesn't have

134
00:07:52.976 --> 00:07:56.956
almost no off-target effects, hits the

135
00:07:57.016 --> 00:08:00.956
target that we're looking for. It's available in a syrup form,

136
00:08:01.056 --> 00:08:04.556
so ideal for infants and young children.

137
00:08:05.136 --> 00:08:08.536
And indeed, this patient had an almost miraculous response with

138
00:08:08.596 --> 00:08:10.446
widespread disease throughout her brain.

139
00:08:11.656 --> 00:08:14.956
Literally had to call her in as she'd been headed home,

140
00:08:15.636 --> 00:08:19.536
sent home for palliation, called her back in, and she went from a child who

141
00:08:19.576 --> 00:08:23.476
was unable to get out of bed to within a

142
00:08:23.516 --> 00:08:27.145
couple of months was walking, talking, and dancing into clinic with

143
00:08:27.276 --> 00:08:30.396
complete resolution of her disease. So this is the dream.

144
00:08:30.476 --> 00:08:33.136
This is what we're looking for. This is the magic bullet.

145
00:08:33.596 --> 00:08:37.516
But in reality, TRK fusions, as an example, are very rare.

146
00:08:38.256 --> 00:08:41.896
They occur in rare tumors or rarely in common

147
00:08:41.956 --> 00:08:45.836
tumors. So the question remained, how useful is doing all

148
00:08:45.876 --> 00:08:49.276
this sequencing for the majority of our brain and other

149
00:08:50.636 --> 00:08:54.476
high-risk cancer patients? And so we published this a couple of years ago

150
00:08:54.556 --> 00:08:58.336
when we looked at what is the result, the impact for our patients.

151
00:08:58.376 --> 00:09:00.816
Essentially, the bottom line is that doing what

152
00:09:02.056 --> 00:09:05.436
we thought is really the most in-depth sequencing that you can do for these

153
00:09:05.476 --> 00:09:09.156
patients, in 71% of these high-risk patients, you can find a

154
00:09:09.176 --> 00:09:12.736
therapeutic target. 5% had a change in diagnosis,

155
00:09:13.156 --> 00:09:16.026
and in those with a therapeutic target, when you do give them

156
00:09:18.196 --> 00:09:20.116
a targeted treatment, in

157
00:09:21.016 --> 00:09:24.796
the majority, we were either seeing disease stabilization or indeed objective

158
00:09:24.856 --> 00:09:27.936
responses, both in the solid tumors, but also,

159
00:09:28.816 --> 00:09:31.176
as per this talk, in the CNS tumors as well.

160
00:09:31.296 --> 00:09:35.256
So the majority who you can match to a targeted drug were

161
00:09:35.276 --> 00:09:38.096
actually getting some clinical benefit of some sort.

162
00:09:39.326 --> 00:09:42.896
But these are very high-risk patients. They've failed multiple therapies.

163
00:09:42.996 --> 00:09:44.836
Are we really helping them in the long term?

164
00:09:44.936 --> 00:09:48.596
Sure, we might see a response, we might see a change in an MRI scan,

165
00:09:48.976 --> 00:09:52.836
but is this really improving the prognosis for these patients, most of whom we

166
00:09:52.856 --> 00:09:55.616
know are not going to survive in the long term?

167
00:09:56.826 --> 00:10:00.556
And so we were able to answer this question more recently when we

168
00:10:00.576 --> 00:10:04.536
actually followed up the first few hundred of these patients on the program,

169
00:10:05.356 --> 00:10:09.196
and followed them in the longer term for those who we'd

170
00:10:09.256 --> 00:10:10.696
followed for at least three years.

171
00:10:11.096 --> 00:10:14.796
And actually, for the first time, we're actually showing that we are improving

172
00:10:14.856 --> 00:10:18.536
their survival, both in terms of progression-free survival and

173
00:10:18.636 --> 00:10:22.506
overall survival. When you look at what we call precision-guided therapy,

174
00:10:22.896 --> 00:10:26.696
so these are patients with a genomic aberration that we can target,

175
00:10:26.756 --> 00:10:28.556
they did get the matched

176
00:10:29.636 --> 00:10:33.416
drug to hit that target. And we compared it with

177
00:10:33.456 --> 00:10:37.376
those who got an unguided therapy, in other words, another novel therapy, perhaps

178
00:10:37.436 --> 00:10:41.156
on a clinical trial, perhaps that their clinician got access to but wasn't matched

179
00:10:41.196 --> 00:10:43.986
to their genomic findings. And there was a clear,

180
00:10:44.836 --> 00:10:48.556
highly significant, both clinically significant but also

181
00:10:48.616 --> 00:10:51.475
statistically significant difference in their outcome.

182
00:10:53.556 --> 00:10:57.536
And also, we're able to try and start to answer some of those questions about what

183
00:10:57.636 --> 00:11:01.116
is it that we should be targeting, like that map of

184
00:11:01.176 --> 00:11:04.596
the image that I showed you of so many different wires, so many different

185
00:11:04.616 --> 00:11:07.356
pathways, in many cases, many different targets.

186
00:11:07.686 --> 00:11:09.856
Which are the ones we should really be going after?

187
00:11:10.896 --> 00:11:14.336
Sometimes we might find a fusion, a mutation,

188
00:11:15.116 --> 00:11:17.896
a copy number variation, high RNA expression.

189
00:11:18.186 --> 00:11:20.276
And we did see, for whatever you're targeting,

190
00:11:21.676 --> 00:11:25.556
some degree of response. So whatever you're targeting, you do see some clinical

191
00:11:25.616 --> 00:11:29.376
benefit. But when we looked at the survival of these patients is when you actually

192
00:11:29.456 --> 00:11:32.696
start to see a clear difference. And it had been

193
00:11:32.736 --> 00:11:34.736
hypothesized

194
00:11:36.096 --> 00:11:39.316
by many different groups and different publications that maybe it's the fusions

195
00:11:39.336 --> 00:11:42.856
that give us the best response, and that's actually what we saw here,

196
00:11:42.916 --> 00:11:44.736
that if you can target a fusion,

197
00:11:45.616 --> 00:11:47.116
then you're actually getting a better response.

198
00:11:47.176 --> 00:11:51.096
Not that you don't respond to other targets, but there is a clear differential

199
00:11:51.276 --> 00:11:51.716
in

200
00:11:53.536 --> 00:11:55.556
clinical benefit based on what you're actually

201
00:11:55.616 --> 00:11:59.592
targeting.And moreover, when we looked

202
00:11:59.632 --> 00:12:02.812
at all the different prognostic factors, when you combine them, you can actually

203
00:12:02.892 --> 00:12:06.522
start to see a real difference. So in particular, if you find something that's

204
00:12:07.212 --> 00:12:07.772
a fusion,

205
00:12:08.612 --> 00:12:12.332
if you're using a drug where you have the highest level of clinical evidence, what

206
00:12:12.372 --> 00:12:12.672
we call--

207
00:12:13.672 --> 00:12:17.452
I think Katie Janeway actually came up with the different

208
00:12:17.512 --> 00:12:21.472
tiers, which we adopted, of Tier 1 clinical evidence, and you use

209
00:12:21.532 --> 00:12:25.142
that early, then you really have a very profound improvement in

210
00:12:25.172 --> 00:12:29.162
survival. And so again, really, I think helpful information to clinicians that

211
00:12:29.212 --> 00:12:32.792
if you're finding a very good target with a good drug that's been

212
00:12:32.852 --> 00:12:35.012
clinically tested, you shouldn't wait.

213
00:12:35.052 --> 00:12:38.871
You should be trying to give that drug to that patient

214
00:12:39.132 --> 00:12:42.272
earlier rather than keeping it in your back pocket and waiting till

215
00:12:43.012 --> 00:12:46.692
they're nearing the end, as I described

216
00:12:46.752 --> 00:12:47.092
earlier.

217
00:12:49.832 --> 00:12:53.552
So we're seeing a clinical benefit, but then, there's some of these

218
00:12:53.712 --> 00:12:57.152
worst of the worst patients where the question has remained, well, are we really

219
00:12:57.192 --> 00:13:00.952
helping those? And in this case, we were looking particularly at those with diffuse

220
00:13:01.012 --> 00:13:04.802
midline gliomas or DIPG, so the worst of the worst brain tumors,

221
00:13:05.432 --> 00:13:07.112
no known effective treatment,

222
00:13:08.132 --> 00:13:11.792
radiation therapy being the only therapy that has any palliative

223
00:13:12.032 --> 00:13:15.492
benefit, but no systemic therapy that we really know improves survival.

224
00:13:16.072 --> 00:13:19.952
And there was a question, are we really helping these patients who we

225
00:13:19.992 --> 00:13:22.492
know are all not going to survive in the long term?

226
00:13:23.072 --> 00:13:26.872
So we looked particularly at these patients with diffuse midline glioma.

227
00:13:26.912 --> 00:13:27.912
This is currently

228
00:13:28.852 --> 00:13:30.572
in press, hopefully will come out soon.

229
00:13:31.022 --> 00:13:34.632
And what we saw when we just looked at overall survival, any patient who got a

230
00:13:34.672 --> 00:13:38.042
precision-guided therapy, we did see a

231
00:13:38.052 --> 00:13:41.652
12 versus 21-month difference in survival, which wasn't

232
00:13:43.472 --> 00:13:46.792
statistically significant. But this is a very

233
00:13:46.832 --> 00:13:50.792
heterogeneous group of patients receiving different treatments at different time

234
00:13:50.892 --> 00:13:54.572
points. So a little bit hard just to compare those two

235
00:13:54.652 --> 00:13:58.592
groups directly. So we tried to try and find a time point where we could

236
00:13:58.632 --> 00:14:00.812
actually match the groups more evenly.

237
00:14:00.892 --> 00:14:04.672
So we looked at those patients who had progression and then got a

238
00:14:04.712 --> 00:14:08.012
different treatment, either re-irradiation, which is now

239
00:14:08.612 --> 00:14:12.552
used by many as a standard of care, or an unguided treatment, as I

240
00:14:12.592 --> 00:14:16.552
described before, or indeed, a precision-guided treatment with

241
00:14:16.612 --> 00:14:20.392
or without radiation therapy. And here we actually see for the

242
00:14:20.452 --> 00:14:23.941
first time that indeed, if we can give a precision-guided treatment to these

243
00:14:24.032 --> 00:14:27.972
patients, we are actually improving both their progression-free survival

244
00:14:28.452 --> 00:14:31.352
and overall survival, compared to just

245
00:14:32.312 --> 00:14:35.452
either an unguided therapy or just re-irradiation.

246
00:14:35.492 --> 00:14:38.082
And I think this is really the first time we've been able to show this.

247
00:14:38.152 --> 00:14:41.522
Indeed, these patients are still not surviving in the long

248
00:14:41.652 --> 00:14:45.562
term, but we are starting to make a difference with these patients if

249
00:14:45.612 --> 00:14:49.492
we can find the right target and the right drug to match them.

250
00:14:49.552 --> 00:14:53.032
How do we improve this further? I think it goes back to what I was saying earlier.

251
00:14:53.072 --> 00:14:56.832
We need combination therapies. We need to be able to hit multiple pathways at the

252
00:14:56.892 --> 00:15:00.092
same time. But at least this is telling us, yes, we are on the right

253
00:15:00.592 --> 00:15:04.552
pathway, and we can potentially make a difference for these patients if we can

254
00:15:04.592 --> 00:15:07.272
find the right drug to match the right target.

255
00:15:09.092 --> 00:15:12.602
So that's all our high-risk patients where we are, I think, starting to make a

256
00:15:12.612 --> 00:15:14.792
difference. We still have a long way to go.

257
00:15:14.872 --> 00:15:17.682
How can we improve those survival curves even more?

258
00:15:17.992 --> 00:15:21.552
And I think combination therapies and novel agents is the way we can do that.

259
00:15:21.572 --> 00:15:24.781
But what about all the other patients, all our non-high-risk patients?

260
00:15:24.852 --> 00:15:27.432
Is this approach actually useful in that setting?

261
00:15:29.232 --> 00:15:29.452
And

262
00:15:30.612 --> 00:15:34.572
again, if we just take a step back and think about the different ways we

263
00:15:34.712 --> 00:15:35.892
use precision medicine,

264
00:15:37.312 --> 00:15:37.692
really,

265
00:15:38.812 --> 00:15:42.792
using that genomic information has now become the standard of care for all brain

266
00:15:42.872 --> 00:15:46.412
tumor patients when we look at what we call DNA methylation profiling.

267
00:15:46.941 --> 00:15:50.492
So many of you will be familiar with this, but for those who aren't, each

268
00:15:50.552 --> 00:15:54.452
gene can be either methylated or unmethylated as a

269
00:15:54.492 --> 00:15:56.372
way to control that gene's expression.

270
00:15:56.822 --> 00:16:00.552
And there's now these chips which you can use that will just look at the whole

271
00:16:00.592 --> 00:16:04.432
genome and tell you which genes are methylated versus unmethylated.

272
00:16:04.852 --> 00:16:08.832
And this was really pioneered by the group at Heidelberg, led by

273
00:16:08.932 --> 00:16:12.892
people like Stefan Pfister and David Jones, where you get now

274
00:16:12.952 --> 00:16:16.372
a report and a readout, which in this case is just

275
00:16:16.472 --> 00:16:17.012
actually--

276
00:16:18.131 --> 00:16:21.962
The image that you often see on these reports actually just infers from that

277
00:16:21.992 --> 00:16:25.592
information the gene expression levels and copy numbers.

278
00:16:25.632 --> 00:16:27.612
So you can see the chromosomes across the bottom,

279
00:16:28.432 --> 00:16:32.172
and you can get some information about chromosome gain or loss or indeed,

280
00:16:32.752 --> 00:16:35.832
gene amplification, in this case, EGFR amplification.

281
00:16:36.272 --> 00:16:37.792
But really what the main

282
00:16:38.632 --> 00:16:41.932
goal of this is to look at that whole pattern of methylation versus

283
00:16:41.992 --> 00:16:45.972
unmethylation across the whole genome and look at that pattern to

284
00:16:46.112 --> 00:16:49.482
see where that tumor matches with other tumors.

285
00:16:49.932 --> 00:16:53.832
And this has been evolved over the last decade since it was first

286
00:16:53.852 --> 00:16:57.682
discovered. And that really is critical information that

287
00:16:57.712 --> 00:17:01.652
we now use to help tell us genomically where this tumor

288
00:17:01.692 --> 00:17:05.642
matches with other tumors. And you essentially get a readout and a score to

289
00:17:05.672 --> 00:17:09.172
tell us how closely, based on that whole DNA methylation

290
00:17:09.212 --> 00:17:13.103
profile, this tumor matches with other tumors and can

291
00:17:13.133 --> 00:17:17.093
then be integrated with the pathological report in about at least

292
00:17:17.133 --> 00:17:20.032
10% of cases can actually change the diagnosis.

293
00:17:22.012 --> 00:17:22.292
And

294
00:17:23.492 --> 00:17:27.312
not just change the diagnosis of the whole group, but actually give you important

295
00:17:27.333 --> 00:17:29.792
information within subgroups of tumors.

296
00:17:30.032 --> 00:17:33.652
So, we now know, for example, or we've known for over a

297
00:17:33.712 --> 00:17:37.432
decade, that medulloblastoma really divides into four

298
00:17:37.652 --> 00:17:41.512
main subgroups of genomically distinct tumors, the WNT,

299
00:17:41.592 --> 00:17:45.412
Sonic Hedgehog, Group 3, and Group 4 tumors, which is

300
00:17:45.892 --> 00:17:49.720
now again the standard of care. ButWe now know within those groups

301
00:17:49.920 --> 00:17:53.820
there are more subgroups. And so with what we call the non-WNT, non-sonic

302
00:17:53.880 --> 00:17:57.640
hedgehog groups, we now know that there are actually eight distinct

303
00:17:57.860 --> 00:18:01.480
genomically very different subgroups of medulloblastoma.

304
00:18:01.960 --> 00:18:05.800
And while we can divide the main subgroups and

305
00:18:05.860 --> 00:18:09.000
tell the difference between them histologically and looking at

306
00:18:09.200 --> 00:18:10.020
IHC,

307
00:18:11.740 --> 00:18:15.620
to really understand these subgroups, you really need DNA methylation profiling

308
00:18:15.660 --> 00:18:19.560
as the only real test that can actually help us understand which

309
00:18:19.620 --> 00:18:23.520
of these subgroups it falls into. And with very different information, for

310
00:18:23.560 --> 00:18:27.440
example, group four, as you can see here, has a very good prognosis

311
00:18:27.480 --> 00:18:30.800
with a very good survival curve. Group eight appears to have a good

312
00:18:30.820 --> 00:18:33.859
prognosis but has these very late relapses.

313
00:18:34.240 --> 00:18:36.080
Group three has a very poor prognosis.

314
00:18:36.140 --> 00:18:38.300
So it gives us very important information.

315
00:18:38.980 --> 00:18:42.889
People, I think, off-study are

316
00:18:42.980 --> 00:18:46.800
trying to now use that information, but we still don't actually know how to

317
00:18:46.860 --> 00:18:50.660
clinically apply it. So we really still need clinical trials that will help us

318
00:18:50.700 --> 00:18:54.140
understand, can we use that prognostic information and different

319
00:18:54.240 --> 00:18:57.840
molecular stratification to change the outcome for these patients.

320
00:18:59.610 --> 00:19:03.550
So that's DNA methylation profiling, but can we do this whole

321
00:19:03.600 --> 00:19:07.280
integrated genomic sequencing for these non-high-risk tumors

322
00:19:07.360 --> 00:19:10.800
and not just change what we

323
00:19:10.840 --> 00:19:14.640
understand from the DNA methylation profile, but understand and even find

324
00:19:14.680 --> 00:19:16.530
treatment targets and change their outcome?

325
00:19:17.100 --> 00:19:20.970
And so we're actually now doing this in Australia for all children with cancer,

326
00:19:21.040 --> 00:19:24.910
not just the high-risk cancers. And when we started to do this, actually had a

327
00:19:24.960 --> 00:19:25.280
bit of

328
00:19:28.760 --> 00:19:32.440
controversy, I should say, from some clinicians said, "We're not going to send you

329
00:19:32.500 --> 00:19:36.060
any low-grade gliomas," for example, "because we know these all do well, and we

330
00:19:36.100 --> 00:19:39.660
really don't need any of this genomic information to help with these patients."

331
00:19:40.740 --> 00:19:41.140
So

332
00:19:42.960 --> 00:19:46.730
as we've started to roll out this non-high-risk cohort, we were doing all this

333
00:19:46.760 --> 00:19:50.220
in-depth DNA sequencing. We looked

334
00:19:50.420 --> 00:19:54.320
specifically at the first group of patients with low-grade gliomas, in this

335
00:19:54.400 --> 00:19:57.560
case, pilocytic astrocytomas. And actually what we found was that in

336
00:19:57.780 --> 00:20:01.480
94% of cases, we could identify a therapeutic target,

337
00:20:02.520 --> 00:20:06.380
the KIAB RAF fusion being the most common and well-established target, but

338
00:20:06.480 --> 00:20:10.320
other molecular targets as well, which importantly, many of these wouldn't actually

339
00:20:10.400 --> 00:20:14.200
be found on more standard panels or more routinely

340
00:20:14.240 --> 00:20:17.780
available clinical tests. So very high

341
00:20:17.900 --> 00:20:20.380
clinical benefit in terms of just

342
00:20:21.220 --> 00:20:25.000
targets we can identify. In other low-grade gliomas, so

343
00:20:25.080 --> 00:20:28.520
not just pilocytic astrocytomas, we found even

344
00:20:28.620 --> 00:20:31.940
more different targets. So again, in this case,

345
00:20:32.200 --> 00:20:36.040
71% where we found actually something targetable, and in many

346
00:20:36.120 --> 00:20:39.500
other cases, not necessarily targetable, but of important prognostic

347
00:20:39.660 --> 00:20:43.060
or diagnostic information that helped change

348
00:20:43.580 --> 00:20:47.460
the treatment for that patient. And indeed, when we surveyed the clinicians for the

349
00:20:47.500 --> 00:20:51.400
vast majority of these non-high-risk, low-grade tumors, they said this

350
00:20:51.420 --> 00:20:54.400
genomic information was actually very helpful for them clinically.

351
00:20:55.960 --> 00:20:59.440
And indeed, it's not surprising because we've now known for a decade that

352
00:20:59.560 --> 00:21:03.380
low-grade gliomas are driven by what we

353
00:21:03.420 --> 00:21:07.400
call a single pathway disease. So they all have aberrations, almost all

354
00:21:07.460 --> 00:21:10.200
in this MAP kinase pathway, which is

355
00:21:11.100 --> 00:21:11.860
important because it's

356
00:21:12.960 --> 00:21:16.580
usually the only target, and it really goes back to this paradigm that we talked

357
00:21:16.620 --> 00:21:20.460
about at the beginning. This is really the low-grade tumors actually fits this very

358
00:21:20.520 --> 00:21:24.400
well, where you have a single pathway, sometimes a single genetic change, and

359
00:21:24.460 --> 00:21:28.180
if we can switch off that change, we can really help these patients.

360
00:21:28.620 --> 00:21:31.900
And this has been shown in those patients with a BRAF

361
00:21:31.920 --> 00:21:35.460
V600E mutation, where a randomized trial was

362
00:21:35.500 --> 00:21:35.960
published

363
00:21:37.060 --> 00:21:40.540
recently in the New England Journal of Medicine, where if we give these patients a

364
00:21:40.560 --> 00:21:44.460
targeted combination therapy, dabrafenib, BRAF inhibitor

365
00:21:44.540 --> 00:21:48.130
with trametinib, a MEK inhibitor, we see a significantly better

366
00:21:48.540 --> 00:21:51.910
both response and survival compared to the standard of care with

367
00:21:51.940 --> 00:21:55.900
chemotherapy. And so these targeted agents have now become the standard of care

368
00:21:55.920 --> 00:21:58.960
for these BRAF V600 mutant tumors.

369
00:22:00.140 --> 00:22:03.980
But if we go back to this pathway, we got to remember, these

370
00:22:04.000 --> 00:22:07.860
BRAF mutant tumors only make up a very small

371
00:22:07.880 --> 00:22:11.740
percent. The majority are actually driven by this BRAF fusion.

372
00:22:12.360 --> 00:22:12.700
And we

373
00:22:13.600 --> 00:22:17.180
now pre-clinically and unfortunately clinically also

374
00:22:17.240 --> 00:22:21.150
know that if you get this paradoxical tumor activation,

375
00:22:21.280 --> 00:22:24.780
if you treat these tumors with a first-generation BRAF

376
00:22:24.820 --> 00:22:25.340
inhibitor.

377
00:22:26.660 --> 00:22:30.600
And so really, we can't use those inhibitors for these most common driver

378
00:22:30.640 --> 00:22:34.600
that we see in these patients. We can use the downstream

379
00:22:34.880 --> 00:22:38.810
targets or MEK, and the studies have now been concluded showing

380
00:22:38.840 --> 00:22:42.680
that MEK inhibitors in these BRAF

381
00:22:42.690 --> 00:22:46.420
fusion-driven tumors or NF1 mutant tumors actually has a

382
00:22:46.460 --> 00:22:50.270
clinical benefit. Seems to be about the same benefit as we see with the

383
00:22:50.360 --> 00:22:54.140
standard of care of chemotherapy, but that hasn't actually been compared

384
00:22:54.180 --> 00:22:58.140
directly in a clinical trial. What's, I think, created

385
00:22:58.160 --> 00:23:01.400
a lot of excitement is now the second-generation inhibitors, and

386
00:23:01.440 --> 00:23:04.700
toverafenib is the lead in this group of

387
00:23:04.980 --> 00:23:08.680
inhibitors, where we can actually target not just the BRAF mutation,

388
00:23:08.860 --> 00:23:12.770
like the first-generation inhibitors, but target the fusion as well,

389
00:23:13.160 --> 00:23:16.580
which you can't do because you get that paradoxical activation if you use

390
00:23:16.640 --> 00:23:20.260
first-generation inhibitors. But toverafenib and others are

391
00:23:20.340 --> 00:23:23.960
pan-RAF inhibitors that can actually successfully switch off this driver.

392
00:23:24.700 --> 00:23:26.260
And what we're seeing now

393
00:23:27.100 --> 00:23:30.940
with these pan-RAF inhibitors is really quite

394
00:23:31.320 --> 00:23:33.520
unprecedented clinical responses,

395
00:23:34.980 --> 00:23:38.920
slightly different depending which criteria you use to measure response, but

396
00:23:38.980 --> 00:23:42.740
really quite dramatic and unprecedented response rates

397
00:23:42.800 --> 00:23:46.380
where normally with these tumors, we're happy just to see a tumor being stable and

398
00:23:46.400 --> 00:23:50.210
not growing. But in this case, we're often seeing tumor regression and

399
00:23:50.240 --> 00:23:54.184
significant clinical benefit.And this is now being compared head-to-head

400
00:23:54.504 --> 00:23:58.464
in a randomized trial as should these inhibitors be the standard of

401
00:23:58.544 --> 00:23:59.724
care for these patients.

402
00:24:01.044 --> 00:24:04.944
So in summary, precision medicine has a growing role, particularly in

403
00:24:04.984 --> 00:24:08.784
childhood brain tumors. It's not just about the magic bullet, but

404
00:24:08.864 --> 00:24:12.764
also a diagnostic test, both in DNA methylation profiling

405
00:24:12.804 --> 00:24:14.904
and the next-generation sequencing.

406
00:24:14.944 --> 00:24:18.704
We are definitely seeing an improvement in outcomes, even in those

407
00:24:18.764 --> 00:24:20.684
highest risk, most aggressive tumors.

408
00:24:21.204 --> 00:24:24.724
But really, almost unexpectedly, it's the low-grade

409
00:24:24.804 --> 00:24:28.604
tumors with that single pathway disease that we are also seeing

410
00:24:28.724 --> 00:24:31.524
very dramatic important clinical benefit.

411
00:24:32.154 --> 00:24:36.104
And I'll just finish by advertising, if any of this is of interest to you at all,

412
00:24:36.744 --> 00:24:40.364
please, you've still got time to come to ISPNO in

413
00:24:40.404 --> 00:24:44.244
Sydney at the end of June, which will be filled

414
00:24:44.284 --> 00:24:47.744
with exciting precision medicine in children's brain

415
00:24:47.784 --> 00:24:49.064
cancer. Thank you.

416
00:24:54.804 --> 00:24:57.944
Thank you, David, for this great talk. He's now open for questions.

417
00:25:00.424 --> 00:25:00.744
Hello.

418
00:25:01.904 --> 00:25:04.424
Ryan Roberts from Nationwide Children's. Great work.

419
00:25:04.924 --> 00:25:08.264
Love what you've been doing. I wanted to ask a question.

420
00:25:08.304 --> 00:25:11.444
I wonder if we're to a point now where we can

421
00:25:11.524 --> 00:25:15.394
operationalize this. I think so much of this has been done in the research setting,

422
00:25:15.424 --> 00:25:19.084
and so often, especially in the rare cancers where this really has the

423
00:25:19.124 --> 00:25:20.434
greatest potential, I think,

424
00:25:21.264 --> 00:25:25.194
we hit up against guidelines where we know exactly what the patient needs,

425
00:25:25.324 --> 00:25:29.054
but the guideline's not there that gives us access to the drug for that

426
00:25:29.064 --> 00:25:29.584
patient.

427
00:25:30.584 --> 00:25:34.204
Do we think that we can get to a place where we operationalize this

428
00:25:34.264 --> 00:25:38.024
process, and the process becomes the guideline for the rare tumors?

429
00:25:39.104 --> 00:25:42.724
Yes, as they say, from your lips to God's

430
00:25:42.824 --> 00:25:46.684
ears. We need to build this in, and I think it's different in different

431
00:25:46.724 --> 00:25:50.124
countries and different jurisdictions. We're looking at that in Australia.

432
00:25:50.164 --> 00:25:53.474
How do we get this built in as the standard of care?

433
00:25:53.474 --> 00:25:57.224
I think even simple things like, again, this is particular to

434
00:25:57.264 --> 00:26:01.004
Australia, we want drugs to be approved, not just as they have been

435
00:26:01.044 --> 00:26:04.164
for decades. Our BRAF inhibitors were improved for melanoma.

436
00:26:04.664 --> 00:26:08.604
What we want is BRAF inhibitors to be approved for patients with BRAF

437
00:26:08.644 --> 00:26:12.524
mutations. And that is starting to happen, but I think it needs us to

438
00:26:12.534 --> 00:26:15.384
advocate for that and speak to the decision-makers.

439
00:26:15.704 --> 00:26:17.004
And I think we have some great examples.

440
00:26:17.924 --> 00:26:21.904
NTRK is linked to the change,

441
00:26:21.984 --> 00:26:25.114
but that's very specific, right? And then we have certain

442
00:26:25.124 --> 00:26:27.284
diseases where we've linked that.

443
00:26:27.304 --> 00:26:31.193
But I wonder if we could create criteria where if you meet this and

444
00:26:31.244 --> 00:26:35.174
this and this, and you actually outline that very, very well, where you have very

445
00:26:35.264 --> 00:26:38.374
high confidence with these criteria that that's the right drug for this patient.

446
00:26:38.484 --> 00:26:42.424
Yeah, exactly. I agree. And I think that needs us to be, as I said, speaking to

447
00:26:42.464 --> 00:26:46.244
those decision-makers and telling them, "This is what you need to be doing,"

448
00:26:46.624 --> 00:26:50.464
particularly for children, particularly children's brain cancer, where they're

449
00:26:50.564 --> 00:26:54.484
all rare diseases, and you're never going to have that randomized trial for most

450
00:26:55.184 --> 00:26:56.044
cases. Yeah.

451
00:26:56.334 --> 00:26:57.904
And even more young adults.

452
00:26:57.984 --> 00:26:58.844
Absolutely.

453
00:27:00.324 --> 00:27:03.784
Shai Israeli from Schneider Children, Tel Aviv University in Israel.

454
00:27:04.324 --> 00:27:07.584
So, this is amazing what the Australians are doing, right?

455
00:27:07.664 --> 00:27:10.864
It doesn't exist anywhere in the world.

456
00:27:10.884 --> 00:27:12.904
So I have two questions related to this.

457
00:27:13.804 --> 00:27:17.364
First is, do you in

458
00:27:17.404 --> 00:27:19.124
addition do germline sequencing?

459
00:27:19.964 --> 00:27:20.804
And the second,

460
00:27:22.604 --> 00:27:23.544
there is a debate

461
00:27:24.544 --> 00:27:27.924
between using whole genome sequencing

462
00:27:27.944 --> 00:27:31.084
approaches to panels. So what

463
00:27:32.104 --> 00:27:32.884
do you think about this?

464
00:27:34.054 --> 00:27:37.904
Yes. So in terms to the first question, yes, we do germline sequencing,

465
00:27:37.984 --> 00:27:41.724
and in fact, just published in clinical cancer research

466
00:27:42.404 --> 00:27:45.924
some of those results. And I think we initially did that, and I think most people

467
00:27:45.984 --> 00:27:46.204
do it,

468
00:27:47.024 --> 00:27:50.244
because you have to do it. In order to understand the somatic environment, you need

469
00:27:50.284 --> 00:27:53.684
to look at the germline. And actually, we had the most

470
00:27:53.744 --> 00:27:57.404
anxiety from clinicians when we started to do that because they didn't want to get

471
00:27:57.464 --> 00:28:00.844
all these germline or didn't know what they're going to do with germline results.

472
00:28:01.544 --> 00:28:05.264
That was when we started. Now that we've been doing it for many years, that

473
00:28:05.324 --> 00:28:08.464
anxiety has dissipated because there's a pretty

474
00:28:08.764 --> 00:28:12.424
simple pathway where they refer to genetic counselors, and it

475
00:28:12.543 --> 00:28:14.664
hasn't created any clinical problems.

476
00:28:15.064 --> 00:28:18.504
And we found, as indeed most people have, a lot more

477
00:28:18.604 --> 00:28:21.924
germline findings than we ever expected.

478
00:28:21.984 --> 00:28:25.764
So about 16% of patients were finding a germline, either

479
00:28:25.904 --> 00:28:29.084
driver or a coincidental finding.

480
00:28:29.113 --> 00:28:32.564
And I think we still need to try and understand how many of them are really driving

481
00:28:32.574 --> 00:28:35.384
the tumors versus how many we're just picking up incidentally.

482
00:28:36.644 --> 00:28:37.064
So yes,

483
00:28:38.284 --> 00:28:41.984
that is part of it. And I think in addition, there's germline

484
00:28:42.004 --> 00:28:45.144
drivers that we haven't identified yet that we still--

485
00:28:46.004 --> 00:28:48.944
Because we're really just looking for germline findings that we know from adult

486
00:28:48.984 --> 00:28:52.184
cancers. But the ones that are specific for pediatric cancers, I

487
00:28:53.084 --> 00:28:54.664
think, need to be still be discovered.

488
00:28:54.774 --> 00:28:57.084
And I forgot your second question.

489
00:28:57.524 --> 00:28:57.824
Panels.

490
00:28:57.844 --> 00:29:00.454
Whole genome versus panel? Yeah. Certainly,

491
00:29:01.644 --> 00:29:05.004
it's very difficult to really accurately compare them.

492
00:29:05.044 --> 00:29:05.264
But

493
00:29:07.524 --> 00:29:11.424
from what we've observed is that everything we've found in a

494
00:29:11.484 --> 00:29:15.364
panel, we'll find in the whole genome, plus more that we

495
00:29:15.404 --> 00:29:16.504
wouldn't find in a panel.

496
00:29:17.004 --> 00:29:19.204
Yes. And the price is getting cheaper, right?

497
00:29:19.624 --> 00:29:23.394
Absolutely. So we actually, when we started, we said, "Well, we'll just do panels.

498
00:29:23.724 --> 00:29:27.684
The whole genome will be for research." We started getting the whole genome

499
00:29:27.724 --> 00:29:31.424
results back faster than the panels, and we actually have stopped doing panels

500
00:29:31.434 --> 00:29:34.324
unless we can't do whole genome for technical reasons. Yeah.

501
00:29:36.004 --> 00:29:37.484
Last short question and short answer.

502
00:29:38.424 --> 00:29:38.784
Of course.

503
00:29:39.664 --> 00:29:43.064
I'm Soumik Saha from Dr. John Presner's lab at the University of Michigan.

