00:31:01.636 --> 00:31:05.396
characteristics briefly and then really focus on our recent work

530
00:31:05.436 --> 00:31:09.096
looking at defining biologic subtypes that are associated with

531
00:31:09.156 --> 00:31:12.346
outcomes following standard frontline chemotherapy.

532
00:31:13.596 --> 00:31:17.406
It will quickly become clear that there is much work to be done in this area, and I

533
00:31:17.436 --> 00:31:21.316
really hope to inspire you. That's a very positive way of saying

534
00:31:21.356 --> 00:31:25.126
that in the bone sarcomas, we're quite behind other cancers and

535
00:31:25.216 --> 00:31:26.836
even other pediatric cancers.

536
00:31:27.836 --> 00:31:29.656
And there are several reasons for this,

537
00:31:30.996 --> 00:31:34.976
the first of which is shown on this slide regarding osteosarcoma.

538
00:31:35.336 --> 00:31:36.916
And you can see that osteosarcoma,

539
00:31:38.136 --> 00:31:41.936
if you look at this histogram, is a disease of teenagers and young adults,

540
00:31:42.516 --> 00:31:46.436
with a few quite younger patients and a few older patients.

541
00:31:46.496 --> 00:31:48.546
And that essentially creates

