722
00:42:26.134 --> 00:42:29.754
for high protein expression and 5.4 for low

723
00:42:30.274 --> 00:42:30.834
expression.

724
00:42:32.594 --> 00:42:32.794
If we

725
00:42:34.254 --> 00:42:35.774
look more at a composite

726
00:42:36.814 --> 00:42:40.674
assessment using both the MYC amplification and

727
00:42:40.734 --> 00:42:44.724
MYC protein, if there's both amplification and high expression,

728
00:42:45.414 --> 00:42:48.104
the overall survival is much

729
00:42:49.114 --> 00:42:51.044
worse with a median survival of one year.

730
00:42:51.994 --> 00:42:55.824
If you have non-amplification and low IHC, then

731
00:42:55.934 --> 00:42:58.934
that median survival goes all the way up to 7.2 years.

732
00:42:59.914 --> 00:43:03.624
These findings, I should have mentioned, are controlling for metastatic

733
00:43:03.674 --> 00:43:07.174
disease, and so we see the same pattern in localized disease.

734
00:43:07.274 --> 00:43:11.154
Although I will point out that the combination of amplification and high

735
00:43:11.194 --> 00:43:13.654
expression is very uncommon in localized disease.

736
00:43:13.714 --> 00:43:17.654
This is really a feature primarily of having advanced or metastatic

737
00:43:17.664 --> 00:43:18.814
disease at diagnosis.

738
00:43:20.614 --> 00:43:24.134
With that, I'll move on to the second bone sarcoma I'll discuss, Ewing sarcoma.

739
00:43:25.354 --> 00:43:27.114
To me, it's really the other bone sarcoma.

740
00:43:27.224 --> 00:43:30.834
I care a lot about Ewing sarcoma as well, but osteosarcoma is my first love.

741
00:43:31.914 --> 00:43:35.574
In Ewing sarcoma, there are about 400 cases per year in the United States.

742
00:43:36.474 --> 00:43:40.374
The five-year event-free and overall survival for localized patients is

743
00:43:40.594 --> 00:43:44.174
78% and 87%. And unlike

744
00:43:44.274 --> 00:43:47.674
osteosarcoma, showing on the right sort of

745
00:43:47.954 --> 00:43:51.834
sequential outcomes of Children's Oncology Group trials,

746
00:43:52.254 --> 00:43:53.514
we've been able to improve

747
00:43:54.334 --> 00:43:56.834
for localized patients event-free survival.

748
00:43:57.534 --> 00:44:01.184
So initially, that's been done through the addition of ifosfamide

749
00:44:01.184 --> 00:44:04.854
etoposide chemotherapy to our sort of

750
00:44:05.094 --> 00:44:08.894
prior standard, which was vincristine, daunorubicin, and cyclophosphamide.

751
00:44:09.554 --> 00:44:12.734
And then also intensifying therapy through interval compression.

752
00:44:13.894 --> 00:44:17.134
In Ewing sarcoma, we do have some clinical prognostic factors.

753
00:44:17.444 --> 00:44:18.624
We look at tumor size.

754
00:44:19.454 --> 00:44:22.263
And in some populations, tumor location.

755
00:44:22.314 --> 00:44:26.014
Although it seems with treatment intensification that we've been able to sort of

756
00:44:26.054 --> 00:44:28.534
what we call treat away that prognostic factor.

757
00:44:29.614 --> 00:44:31.174
Here as well, we've looked at necrosis.

758
00:44:31.234 --> 00:44:34.584
In other words, the number of dead cells after we've removed the tumor following

759
00:44:34.594 --> 00:44:38.574
some upfront chemotherapy. But again, these are really observations

760
00:44:38.594 --> 00:44:41.074
of bad behavior rather than correlation with underlying

761
00:44:41.094 --> 00:44:43.904
biology. Unlike

762
00:44:44.714 --> 00:44:47.594
osteosarcoma, Ewing sarcoma has a very simple genome.

763
00:44:48.314 --> 00:44:50.814
It's characterized by a canonical fusion between

764
00:44:51.294 --> 00:44:54.894
EWSR1 and FLI1. Most often, those are FET-ETS

765
00:44:54.934 --> 00:44:55.434
fusions.

766
00:44:56.294 --> 00:45:00.174
And then additional mutations or other types of changes are quite

767
00:45:00.234 --> 00:45:04.174
uncommon. With STAG2 and TP53 being the

768
00:45:04.234 --> 00:45:06.574
only two recurrently mutated genes.

769
00:45:07.074 --> 00:45:07.894
We do see some

770
00:45:09.234 --> 00:45:13.174
sort of arm level copy number changes in chromosome one

771
00:45:13.294 --> 00:45:17.054
and chromosome eight. So here we took a very different

772
00:45:17.064 --> 00:45:19.614
approach to what I described previously.

773
00:45:19.654 --> 00:45:23.134
We looked at patients enrolled on the three most recent Children's Oncology Group

774
00:45:23.154 --> 00:45:26.894
phase-three trials of treatment in newly diagnosed patients with

775
00:45:27.054 --> 00:45:30.934
localized Ewing sarcoma. We used an assay that was

776
00:45:30.994 --> 00:45:34.934
actually developed for circulating tumor DNA called Trans eq, which

777
00:45:34.974 --> 00:45:38.274
combines low-passage whole genome sequencing

778
00:45:39.274 --> 00:45:43.174
with a very small panel to detect some of

779
00:45:43.234 --> 00:45:43.594
these

780
00:45:45.854 --> 00:45:46.594
short variants.

781
00:45:47.714 --> 00:45:51.234
And we used as well STAG2 immunohistochemistry, which I will not

782
00:45:51.274 --> 00:45:51.734
discuss.

783
00:45:52.674 --> 00:45:55.194
The Trans eq panel is shown on the right.

784
00:45:56.174 --> 00:45:59.994
And the reason we did this is because we were working with

785
00:46:00.004 --> 00:46:02.114
samples

786
00:46:03.214 --> 00:46:05.674
with very small amounts of tumor remaining.

787
00:46:06.554 --> 00:46:10.434
So of a patient population of 1,674

788
00:46:10.554 --> 00:46:13.434
from these three prior prospective trials,

789
00:46:14.254 --> 00:46:17.954
we had about 354 unique cases. But most of

790
00:46:18.034 --> 00:46:21.834
those were FFPE samples sitting in the Children's Oncology

791
00:46:21.914 --> 00:46:24.994
Tumor Bank, where we only had three slides available

792
00:46:25.354 --> 00:46:26.793
for our assays.

793
00:46:27.874 --> 00:46:31.494
We were able, with those three slides, to detect the canonical Ewing fusion in

794
00:46:31.774 --> 00:46:33.734
282 patients.

795
00:46:34.714 --> 00:46:38.534
And the 19% here on the upper right where we did

796
00:46:38.544 --> 00:46:41.634
not detect the canonical fusion, I think it's not that they didn't have Ewing

797
00:46:41.694 --> 00:46:45.554
sarcoma. It's more that the input material was such

798
00:46:45.654 --> 00:46:47.634
poor quality that we were not able to detect it.

799
00:46:47.694 --> 00:46:50.753
So those cases were eliminated from the analysis.

800
00:46:52.454 --> 00:46:53.834
What we see here is that

801
00:46:54.634 --> 00:46:58.314
recurrent copy number alterations, which are those segmental copy number

802
00:46:58.324 --> 00:46:59.124
abnormalities,

803
00:46:59.994 --> 00:47:03.724
STAG2 mutation, and TP53 mutations are all

804
00:47:03.754 --> 00:47:07.704
associated with an increased risk of relapse when looked at individually

805
00:47:07.734 --> 00:47:11.334
in this disease. These are sort of reverse survival curves.

806
00:47:11.374 --> 00:47:15.144
I'll just point that out. So over time, we're looking at what's your

807
00:47:15.174 --> 00:47:17.264
percentage chance of recurrence.

808
00:47:19.014 --> 00:47:22.934
And then when we look in a multivariable model, it's really STAG2 mutation

809
00:47:22.994 --> 00:47:26.234
that's associated with an increased risk of relapse in this patient

810
00:47:26.254 --> 00:47:30.014
population. We also see that interval-compressed chemotherapy is

811
00:47:30.054 --> 00:47:33.814
associated with a decreased risk of recurrence, which is what we had hoped to

812
00:47:33.874 --> 00:47:37.194
see. And for each year of age, there's

813
00:47:37.754 --> 00:47:41.314
the hazard ratio of 1.1 for an association

814
00:47:41.894 --> 00:47:43.164
of an increased risk of relapse.

815
00:47:44.034 --> 00:47:47.294
Tumor volume, which I had mentioned has been shown to be

816
00:47:47.614 --> 00:47:51.314
associated with outcome in this disease, was only available for a subset of these

817
00:47:51.354 --> 00:47:51.814
patients.

818
00:47:52.674 --> 00:47:56.514
But when we did look at tumor volume, a larger tumor was

819
00:47:56.554 --> 00:48:00.474
associated with a risk of STAG2 mutation, but STAG2 mutation

820
00:48:00.774 --> 00:48:04.274
retained its similar increased risk of relapse in a

821
00:48:04.294 --> 00:48:08.282
multivariable model in that subset of tumors.So with

822
00:48:08.342 --> 00:48:12.142
these results, we're actually getting to the point where we can start to

823
00:48:12.182 --> 00:48:14.562
create a model of Ewing sarcoma risk groups.

824
00:48:15.662 --> 00:48:19.602
We can create a model as shown on the left, where we actually

825
00:48:19.882 --> 00:48:23.142
provide the variables that we think are most

826
00:48:23.961 --> 00:48:26.452
likely to define outcome. And here we

827
00:48:27.522 --> 00:48:31.342
said STAG2 mutation, TP53 mutation, or other recurrent

828
00:48:31.402 --> 00:48:34.202
copy number alterations or no alterations at all.

829
00:48:35.042 --> 00:48:38.792
And as you can see in this recurrence-free survival curve,

830
00:48:39.122 --> 00:48:42.562
if you have no alterations at all, your recurrence-free survival is

831
00:48:42.642 --> 00:48:46.382
approaching that 90% mark, where you start to think about strategies

832
00:48:46.422 --> 00:48:47.062
like dose

833
00:48:48.042 --> 00:48:49.782
de-escalation of your chemotherapy.

834
00:48:51.042 --> 00:48:52.882
Or we can ask the computer to create a model.

835
00:48:53.552 --> 00:48:55.542
And when we ask the computer to create a model,

836
00:48:56.922 --> 00:49:00.462
the model that gets created includes these molecular

837
00:49:00.522 --> 00:49:02.602
abnormalities, but also clinical features.

838
00:49:02.942 --> 00:49:05.702
And so the lowest risk patients here have a younger age,

839
00:49:06.602 --> 00:49:10.362
have extraosseous tumors, so not all Ewing sarcomas are bone

840
00:49:10.422 --> 00:49:13.082
sarcomas, and have smaller tumor volume.

841
00:49:13.382 --> 00:49:15.382
So what that tells us is that we need to

842
00:49:16.262 --> 00:49:19.882
do a little bit more work with our modeling of outcomes

843
00:49:20.282 --> 00:49:23.822
and integrate some of our clinical features to a greater

844
00:49:23.862 --> 00:49:26.022
extent, and we are working on that.

845
00:49:27.462 --> 00:49:31.322
So I just want to say a word about second malignancies and the findings in this

846
00:49:31.402 --> 00:49:32.502
study around that

847
00:49:34.622 --> 00:49:38.472
complication of treatment. So 3% to 4% of patients treated for

848
00:49:38.542 --> 00:49:41.242
Ewing sarcoma will develop second malignant neoplasms.

849
00:49:41.522 --> 00:49:45.162
The majority of those are related to the chemotherapy agents and

850
00:49:45.262 --> 00:49:48.382
are liquid malignancies, very characteristic

851
00:49:48.662 --> 00:49:49.342
leukemias.

852
00:49:50.592 --> 00:49:52.302
And there's an interesting finding in this study.

853
00:49:52.362 --> 00:49:55.912
If you look at the group of patients who have these recurrent copy number

854
00:49:56.002 --> 00:49:59.502
alterations, I told you that there's an increased risk of

855
00:49:59.512 --> 00:50:03.042
relapse if you have recurrent copy number alterations.

856
00:50:03.062 --> 00:50:06.502
However, if you look at event-free survival, the curves are

857
00:50:06.862 --> 00:50:08.302
overlapping. So there's no

858
00:50:10.122 --> 00:50:13.662
decrease in

859
00:50:13.682 --> 00:50:16.722
event-free survival if you have recurrent copy number alterations.

860
00:50:18.061 --> 00:50:21.862
So we decided to look at cumulative incidence of second malignant neoplasms.

861
00:50:22.382 --> 00:50:25.792
And what you actually see here is that if you have

862
00:50:26.042 --> 00:50:26.782
recurrent

863
00:50:27.622 --> 00:50:30.882
copy number alterations, you have a lower risk of second malignant

864
00:50:30.902 --> 00:50:34.822
neoplasms. If you don't have recurrent copy number alterations, you have a

865
00:50:34.882 --> 00:50:38.062
higher risk of second malignant neoplasms.

866
00:50:39.122 --> 00:50:39.652
We don't

867
00:50:42.382 --> 00:50:42.962
really know if the

868
00:50:44.822 --> 00:50:47.422
sort of underlying reason for this is biologic or not.

869
00:50:47.822 --> 00:50:50.742
But more likely, this is an issue of competing risks.

870
00:50:50.942 --> 00:50:53.442
Because relapse

871
00:50:54.142 --> 00:50:57.642
which generally leads to dying of disease and getting a

872
00:50:57.702 --> 00:51:00.982
second malignancy are in competition with each other.

873
00:51:01.062 --> 00:51:04.802
So you have to not relapse and not die of your disease in order to get a second

874
00:51:04.822 --> 00:51:05.342
malignancy.

875
00:51:06.322 --> 00:51:09.282
So we think what's happening here is that we're revealing

876
00:51:10.962 --> 00:51:14.782
potentially a higher risk of second malignancies in our patients with

877
00:51:14.902 --> 00:51:18.492
sort of good biology disease because they're not going on to progress and

878
00:51:18.562 --> 00:51:20.282
die of their cancer.

879
00:51:21.102 --> 00:51:22.862
But much more work needs to be done here.

880
00:51:22.882 --> 00:51:25.662
It's a very challenging area to work on.

881
00:51:25.922 --> 00:51:29.702
So in conclusion, osteosarcoma and Ewing sarcoma have molecular subtypes defined

882
00:51:29.722 --> 00:51:31.262
by single gene alterations

883
00:51:32.082 --> 00:51:34.002
associated with clinically important outcomes.

884
00:51:34.282 --> 00:51:37.882
For osteosarcoma, MYC amplification and protein expression

885
00:51:38.862 --> 00:51:40.962
are associated with worse overall survival.

886
00:51:41.351 --> 00:51:43.362
These findings do need to be validated.

887
00:51:43.642 --> 00:51:47.292
These are really convenience cohorts, not all universally treated,

888
00:51:47.382 --> 00:51:50.772
although in osteosarcoma, sort of doesn't matter what chemotherapy you give,

889
00:51:50.782 --> 00:51:54.142
outcomes are the same. But indeed, those need to be validated.

890
00:51:54.262 --> 00:51:57.802
In Ewing sarcoma, STAG2 mutation and maybe protein

891
00:51:57.862 --> 00:52:01.402
expression, which I didn't have a time to discuss here, is associated with an

892
00:52:01.442 --> 00:52:03.962
increased risk of recurrence and worse

893
00:52:05.102 --> 00:52:06.042
overall survival.

894
00:52:07.422 --> 00:52:08.512
And the

895
00:52:09.842 --> 00:52:13.582
study I showed you is in fact a validation of previously reported results.

896
00:52:13.642 --> 00:52:15.462
So we actually think that's ready for

897
00:52:16.842 --> 00:52:18.762
action in the clinical trial setting.

898
00:52:19.382 --> 00:52:21.892
But there are remaining questions and ongoing future work.

899
00:52:22.742 --> 00:52:26.541
There are other candidate molecular biomarkers of treatment response and outcome in

900
00:52:26.582 --> 00:52:30.522
osteosarcoma and Ewing sarcoma, such as RNA signatures, epigenomics,

901
00:52:30.582 --> 00:52:31.582
and LOH burden.

902
00:52:33.122 --> 00:52:37.042
So we're really now starting to look, especially in osteosarcoma, beyond

903
00:52:37.162 --> 00:52:40.842
single gene alterations. And that, just to

904
00:52:40.922 --> 00:52:42.662
answer a question that was asked before,

905
00:52:43.602 --> 00:52:47.242
more comprehensive sequencing than the targeted sequencing I showed you is needed

906
00:52:47.302 --> 00:52:48.122
for most of those.

907
00:52:49.022 --> 00:52:52.482
So are these molecular subgroups independent of each other?

908
00:52:52.702 --> 00:52:55.382
Can we apply molecular biomarkers in clinical practice?

909
00:52:55.762 --> 00:52:58.702
Can we leverage insight for therapeutic advances?

910
00:52:59.002 --> 00:53:02.522
And really now we're having to use collaborative approaches to building

911
00:53:02.542 --> 00:53:06.042
clinico-genomic data sets in rare cancers in this disease.

912
00:53:06.542 --> 00:53:09.682
And these are just two ongoing projects that I'm working on.

913
00:53:09.782 --> 00:53:13.322
One of them is a direct-to-patient engagement called Participant Engagement in

914
00:53:13.402 --> 00:53:16.502
Cancer Genomic Sequencing Network. It's funded by the Cancer Moonshot.

915
00:53:16.922 --> 00:53:20.502
And we directly enroll patients online, collected

916
00:53:21.502 --> 00:53:25.262
tumor samples and medical records from their treating institutions, and are

917
00:53:25.322 --> 00:53:29.302
starting to analyze the genomic data here and actually are hoping to

918
00:53:29.342 --> 00:53:31.262
do our first data sharing in the next

919
00:53:32.162 --> 00:53:32.922
six months or so.

920
00:53:34.462 --> 00:53:38.422
In addition, just started is a breakthrough

921
00:53:38.482 --> 00:53:40.642
cancer team focused on osteosarcoma,

922
00:53:41.482 --> 00:53:45.462
and this has a major data-sharing component where we're trying

923
00:53:45.502 --> 00:53:49.002
to look beyond just these single gene abnormalities I've told you about for

924
00:53:49.022 --> 00:53:51.682
osteosarcoma. And then in Ewing sarcoma,

925
00:53:52.482 --> 00:53:56.462
the Children's Oncology Group Molecular Characterization Initiative, which I'm

926
00:53:56.522 --> 00:53:58.402
happy to tell you more about if you're curious,

927
00:53:59.282 --> 00:54:03.262
is now enrolling patients with metastatic Ewing sarcoma and round

928
00:54:03.302 --> 00:54:07.222
cell sarcomas of bone and localized soft tissue Ewing sarcomas and round cells.

929
00:54:07.282 --> 00:54:11.120
And we're hoping to expand it to localized Ewing sarcoma as well.And then

930
00:54:11.150 --> 00:54:14.470
through this initiative there will be RNA

931
00:54:14.510 --> 00:54:18.380
sequencing, methylation profiling, and whole genome

932
00:54:18.450 --> 00:54:20.640
sequencing. Sorry, whole exome sequencing.

933
00:54:21.430 --> 00:54:24.550
So with that, I'd like to acknowledge, in particular, the patients and families who

934
00:54:24.570 --> 00:54:28.390
participated in our molecular studies, members of the laboratory

935
00:54:28.530 --> 00:54:30.970
collaborators, and the Children's Oncology Group. Thank you.

936
00:54:36.690 --> 00:54:40.470
Thanks so much, Katie. Questions for Dr. Janeway? Please come to the microphone.

937
00:54:47.470 --> 00:54:48.390
I promise these guys aren't-

938
00:54:48.410 --> 00:54:52.090
Katie, great talk, and obviously dear to my heart as well.

939
00:54:52.710 --> 00:54:56.150
Do you think we have enough information to start deescalating

