00:56:41.430 --> 00:56:43.490
Dr. Janeway, I have a clinical question.

972
00:56:44.010 --> 00:56:47.010
So when we stop typing the pediatric

973
00:56:47.590 --> 00:56:50.590
cancers, do we need to consider about the

974
00:56:51.330 --> 00:56:54.410
emerging drug targets developed for

975
00:56:55.070 --> 00:56:58.990
adult cancers, such as the targets for ADCs

976
00:56:59.050 --> 00:57:01.150
and bispecific antibodies?

977
00:57:01.950 --> 00:57:05.160
Yeah. So great question. The question just is

978
00:57:05.230 --> 00:57:08.650
about drug development for patients of the

979
00:57:08.750 --> 00:57:10.380
age where

980
00:57:11.270 --> 00:57:13.310
these patients are developing cancer.

981
00:57:13.450 --> 00:57:17.290
So, in fact, we were having a little conversation up here before the

982
00:57:17.310 --> 00:57:21.239
session began about the challenge of sort of teenagers and young adults with

983
00:57:21.270 --> 00:57:25.230
cancer. And I think the challenges are

984
00:57:25.290 --> 00:57:26.210
many.

985
00:57:27.210 --> 00:57:30.670
One in the sort of genomic space or precision medicine space we're

986
00:57:30.690 --> 00:57:34.110
discussing here, a project like Zero Childhood Cancer is

987
00:57:34.170 --> 00:57:34.810
phenomenal.

988
00:57:35.710 --> 00:57:38.489
But until now, although David tells me, Dr.

989
00:57:38.570 --> 00:57:42.550
Ziegler tells me that it's improving now have barely been focused

990
00:57:42.570 --> 00:57:46.390
on the pediatric patient population, which only includes maybe

991
00:57:46.450 --> 00:57:49.790
two-thirds of patients with osteosarcoma and Ewing sarcoma, for example.

992
00:57:50.890 --> 00:57:52.690
And so our

993
00:57:54.110 --> 00:57:57.959
efforts to collect large patient populations, which is what we need

994
00:57:57.990 --> 00:58:01.470
to do in this precision medicine and genomic space, particularly in a complex

995
00:58:01.550 --> 00:58:05.190
cancer, are challenged by this split between two silos.

996
00:58:05.810 --> 00:58:07.790
In drug development, we have a similar problem.

997
00:58:08.690 --> 00:58:09.170
And

998
00:58:10.590 --> 00:58:13.130
the problem is on multiple levels.

999
00:58:14.310 --> 00:58:15.050
First of all,

1000
00:58:16.890 --> 00:58:18.150
at the institutional level,

1001
00:58:19.330 --> 00:58:22.450
there are some challenges, although many of us work very hard on

1002
00:58:22.490 --> 00:58:23.330
that.

1003
00:58:24.340 --> 00:58:28.239
Accessing trials, for example, from my medical oncology colleagues that I

1004
00:58:28.309 --> 00:58:32.300
have open in pediatric oncology that are focused on osteosarcoma and the same is

1005
00:58:32.300 --> 00:58:35.050
true the other way. So in the United States, the FDA has said

1006
00:58:35.930 --> 00:58:38.970
trials of new drugs like ADCs that are relevant in

1007
00:58:39.050 --> 00:58:42.770
osteosarcoma or even Ewing sarcoma should go down to age 12.

1008
00:58:43.510 --> 00:58:43.710
But

1009
00:58:44.830 --> 00:58:48.810
our very small patient population is competing with a flood of

1010
00:58:48.850 --> 00:58:51.210
carcinoma patients who are enrolling on those trials.

1011
00:58:51.250 --> 00:58:53.150
So it gets hard to get the patient in.

1012
00:58:53.260 --> 00:58:57.220
And if you do get the patient in, it's one or two patients out of 75,

1013
00:58:57.250 --> 00:58:59.190
and they're using those trials to look for signals.

1014
00:58:59.230 --> 00:59:03.070
So you can't get a signal with one or two patients, particularly in a biologically

1015
00:59:03.150 --> 00:59:05.530
complex disease. So that's a problem.

1016
00:59:06.490 --> 00:59:06.950
Second,

1017
00:59:07.870 --> 00:59:11.790
there is a pediatric drug development in the United States and in Europe sort of,

1018
00:59:11.860 --> 00:59:15.250
and other places, focused on pediatric drug development, but it's really fit for

1019
00:59:15.350 --> 00:59:17.130
purpose for small people,

1020
00:59:18.130 --> 00:59:22.010
like liquid formulation, dosing in small people.

1021
00:59:22.530 --> 00:59:26.450
And that actually if anything,

1022
00:59:26.530 --> 00:59:30.480
maybe delays the rate at which our adolescents and

1023
00:59:30.510 --> 00:59:33.070
young adults get access to these drugs.

1024
00:59:33.130 --> 00:59:36.270
So there's a lot to be worked on there. Thank you for asking the question.

1025
00:59:36.670 --> 00:59:36.950
Thank you.

1026
00:59:37.910 --> 00:59:38.790
Thanks.

1027
00:59:51.870 --> 00:59:55.850
Okay. It's my pleasure to round out this session with the discussion of precision

1028
00:59:55.890 --> 00:59:59.580
medicine in childhood leukemias, and we'll touch on important topics today in

1029
00:59:59.650 --> 01:00:03.190
ALL, AML, and some rare pediatric myeloid leukemias as well.

1030
01:00:04.270 --> 01:00:07.610
So I don't have to remind this audience that acute lymphoblastic leukemia or ALL,

1031
01:00:07.670 --> 01:00:11.660
has really been a major success story for us in pediatric oncology, and you can

1032
01:00:11.670 --> 01:00:15.170
see here shown in these survival curves over the past 50 years, we've really made

1033
01:00:15.190 --> 01:00:18.850
dramatic improvements in event-free and overall survival of our patients.

1034
01:00:19.250 --> 01:00:22.710
And this has largely been due to appropriate risk intensification

1035
01:00:23.290 --> 01:00:27.090
based on underlying genomics as well as measurable residual disease or

1036
01:00:27.190 --> 01:00:29.370
MRD at the end of induction chemotherapy.

1037
01:00:30.070 --> 01:00:34.007
And we nowWe're in an era for many of our patients with lowest risk ALL, we're able

1038
01:00:34.078 --> 01:00:37.888
to preserve good cure rates even with the RBD intensification.

1039
01:00:37.888 --> 01:00:41.678
And I think for this patient population, this remains a major goal, even if you

1040
01:00:41.738 --> 01:00:44.418
will consider this a bit of precision medicine.

1041
01:00:44.438 --> 01:00:47.698
And we certainly in recent years, and we'll touch on this in the coming slides,

1042
01:00:47.758 --> 01:00:51.098
have appreciated the power of immunotherapy, and I would like to argue with you

1043
01:00:51.138 --> 01:00:54.098
that this is also a good method of precision medicine therapy.

1044
01:00:54.498 --> 01:00:58.358
But we are also very interested in moving forward how to combine antibody-based

1045
01:00:58.618 --> 01:01:01.118
immunotherapies now also with targeted inhibitors.

1046
01:01:02.368 --> 01:01:06.348
And so we certainly know through major collaborative team science and collaborative

1047
01:01:06.438 --> 01:01:10.378
work done in very sophisticated next generation sequencing,

1048
01:01:10.418 --> 01:01:14.038
that childhood ALL, both in the B subset and the T subset, are

1049
01:01:14.138 --> 01:01:17.878
incredibly genetically heterogeneous and shown here on the right are just some

1050
01:01:17.898 --> 01:01:20.998
examples of the many subtypes within childhood B-ALL.

1051
01:01:21.718 --> 01:01:25.498
And this has been a very exciting time, I think, to marry the important advances

1052
01:01:25.538 --> 01:01:29.238
that we have made in genetic characterization of childhood ALL, also with

1053
01:01:29.278 --> 01:01:33.138
preclinical functional validation to try to understand which of these subtypes may

1054
01:01:33.158 --> 01:01:35.248
be targetable by precision medicine approaches.

1055
01:01:36.058 --> 01:01:39.288
I think what remains difficult for us in ALL, however, particularly in

1056
01:01:39.318 --> 01:01:43.258
T-ALL, is that many of these subtypes are associated with chemotherapy

1057
01:01:43.338 --> 01:01:46.688
resistance and poor outcomes, but we don't yet know how to drug them.

1058
01:01:46.718 --> 01:01:50.618
And so a lot of work is continuing to go on to try to understand how we can

1059
01:01:50.658 --> 01:01:54.418
match the right patient to the right medicine within these high-risk subtypes of

1060
01:01:54.478 --> 01:01:58.178
ALL. And even when we have very compelling biology and

1061
01:01:58.198 --> 01:02:01.918
rationale that suggests that a targeted therapy may be particularly relevant for a

1062
01:02:01.958 --> 01:02:05.758
child with high-risk leukemia, I think as this group unfortunately also

1063
01:02:05.798 --> 01:02:09.618
well knows, access to most promising targeted therapies has remained a major

1064
01:02:09.658 --> 01:02:11.498
challenge for us in pediatric oncology.

1065
01:02:13.138 --> 01:02:16.518
So I'll start out by talking a little bit about BCR-ABL-rearranged or Philadelphia

1066
01:02:16.598 --> 01:02:20.518
chromosome positive ALL, which really for us in pediatric oncology has been a major

1067
01:02:20.578 --> 01:02:24.378
paradigm for precision medicine really for the past 25 years.

1068
01:02:25.018 --> 01:02:28.648
We now learned in the early 2000s through clinical trials done by the Children's

1069
01:02:28.698 --> 01:02:32.458
Oncology Group, as well as our colleagues in Europe, that the addition of the

1070
01:02:32.498 --> 01:02:36.308
first-generation tyrosine kinase inhibitor imatinib to chemotherapy could

1071
01:02:36.318 --> 01:02:39.648
dramatically improve event-free survival for these patients and

1072
01:02:39.698 --> 01:02:43.458
importantly, spare some of these children from the toxicity of hematopoietic stem

1073
01:02:43.518 --> 01:02:45.358
cell transplantation in first remission.

1074
01:02:46.338 --> 01:02:49.438
Continued work through the COG and other consortia have now credentialed

1075
01:02:49.498 --> 01:02:53.268
second-generation inhibitors such as dasatinib when added to chemotherapy.

1076
01:02:53.958 --> 01:02:57.418
Although paradoxically, we have not seen an improved outcome for patients treated

1077
01:02:57.458 --> 01:03:01.418
with dasatinib compared to imatinib in the PH-positive space for reasons

1078
01:03:01.438 --> 01:03:05.018
that we don't fully understand, given the potential for greater molecular

1079
01:03:05.078 --> 01:03:08.078
remissions with dasatinib and also greater CNS penetration.

1080
01:03:08.998 --> 01:03:12.958
These clinical trials have also through robust correlative biology studies,

1081
01:03:13.018 --> 01:03:16.318
also allowed us to define the prognostic impact of important

1082
01:03:16.398 --> 01:03:20.287
co-mutations in PH-positive ALL, including Ikaros deletions and

1083
01:03:20.318 --> 01:03:24.058
other transcription factor deletions that we think incrementally may add to the

1084
01:03:24.078 --> 01:03:27.818
poor prognosis of these patients, although we don't fully yet know how we might

1085
01:03:27.878 --> 01:03:31.598
overcome those barriers. And I think that the paradigm of successful

1086
01:03:31.678 --> 01:03:35.578
precision medicine in PH-positive ALL has been a huge success and

1087
01:03:35.598 --> 01:03:39.498
has also really inspired us to try to understand how we may now apply precision

1088
01:03:39.538 --> 01:03:43.358
medicine approaches to other potentially targetable high-risk subsets of

1089
01:03:43.398 --> 01:03:44.028
childhood ALL.

1090
01:03:45.488 --> 01:03:49.118
And so, of course, the natural succession plan was to look at what we now call the

1091
01:03:49.218 --> 01:03:53.198
Philadelphia chromosome-like or PH-like ALL subtype,

1092
01:03:53.598 --> 01:03:57.578
which we now know is an incredibly common subtype of B-ALL across

1093
01:03:57.618 --> 01:04:01.317
the age spectrum that is associated with high rates of chemotherapy resistance,

1094
01:04:01.388 --> 01:04:03.978
MRD positivity, and ultimately relapse.

1095
01:04:04.618 --> 01:04:07.938
We also have learned through collaborative genomic sequencing efforts that the

1096
01:04:07.978 --> 01:04:10.958
PH-like ALL subtypes are also driven by a variety of

1097
01:04:11.018 --> 01:04:14.638
non-BCR-ABL rearrangements that also activate constitutive

1098
01:04:14.698 --> 01:04:18.398
cytokine receptor or kinase signaling, and it is hypothesized that these

1099
01:04:18.438 --> 01:04:22.238
patients may similarly benefit from the addition of TKIs to chemotherapy to

1100
01:04:22.298 --> 01:04:23.958
improve relapse risk and survival.

1101
01:04:25.518 --> 01:04:29.338
We now know that there are more than 80 different discrete fusions within PH-like

1102
01:04:29.358 --> 01:04:33.158
ALL over the past 15 years. This is an incredibly heterogeneous

1103
01:04:33.168 --> 01:04:37.018
subtype now. But for all practical purposes, we can bin patients with

1104
01:04:37.078 --> 01:04:40.058
PH-like ALL into one of two major categories.

1105
01:04:40.138 --> 01:04:43.978
About 70% of which harbor alterations in the JAK-STAT pathway are

1106
01:04:44.018 --> 01:04:47.438
predominantly rearrangements in the cytokine receptor-like factor two or

1107
01:04:47.458 --> 01:04:50.898
CRLF2 gene, but also fusions involving JAK2 or the

1108
01:04:50.938 --> 01:04:54.658
erythropoietin receptor. And based on robust preclinical data and

1109
01:04:54.718 --> 01:04:58.478
anecdotal emerging clinical data, we think that these patients may particularly

1110
01:04:58.518 --> 01:05:02.238
benefit from the addition of JAK inhibitors to chemotherapy such as ruxolitinib.

1111
01:05:03.148 --> 01:05:07.138
We also know that another 10 to 15% of patients harbor mutually exclusive

1112
01:05:07.218 --> 01:05:10.878
alterations in what we call ABL class genes involving fusions of

1113
01:05:10.938 --> 01:05:14.658
ABL1, ABL2, CSF1R, PDGFR beta. And

1114
01:05:14.718 --> 01:05:18.398
similar to PH-positive ALL, we think that these patients may particularly benefit

1115
01:05:18.418 --> 01:05:21.708
from the addition of SRC-ABL inhibitors such as imatinib or dasatinib.

1116
01:05:22.398 --> 01:05:26.018
And then finally, there's sort of a grab bag over here if you will, of N of one

1117
01:05:26.078 --> 01:05:30.038
type alterations that activate kinase signaling and may similarly be

1118
01:05:30.278 --> 01:05:34.138
susceptible to targeted TKIs, although we don't yet know if these are fully

1119
01:05:34.198 --> 01:05:35.718
considered PH-like or not.

1120
01:05:37.038 --> 01:05:40.718
And so to address some of these questions based on robust preclinical data and

1121
01:05:40.758 --> 01:05:44.078
translating that to the clinic through our children's oncology group, we have

1122
01:05:44.138 --> 01:05:48.078
recently conducted a Phase II clinical trial called AALL 1521

1123
01:05:48.458 --> 01:05:52.258
that was a single-arm study in which we non-randomly added ruxolitinib, a JAK

1124
01:05:52.298 --> 01:05:55.998
inhibitor, to chemotherapy for patients with newly diagnosed PH-like

1125
01:05:56.058 --> 01:05:59.398
ALL harboring those CRLF2 rearrangements or other JAK pathway

1126
01:05:59.478 --> 01:06:03.418
alterations. In the Phase I component of this study, we explored six different

1127
01:06:03.438 --> 01:06:07.078
dose levels of ruxolitinib to identify a safe and tolerable dose in the frontline

1128
01:06:07.118 --> 01:06:10.658
with multi-agent chemotherapy. And in the second Part II phase, we are

1129
01:06:10.698 --> 01:06:14.058
exploring the efficacy of patients treated at the recommended Phase II dose of

1130
01:06:14.078 --> 01:06:18.018
ruxolitinib with chemotherapy. This study completed accrual about three years

1131
01:06:18.058 --> 01:06:21.838
ago, and we are eagerly awaiting efficacy results in the mature readout,

1132
01:06:21.998 --> 01:06:25.890
hopefully later this year.At the same time that we were conducting

1133
01:06:25.900 --> 01:06:29.830
this study for PH-like ALL, we also were continuing to conduct

1134
01:06:29.870 --> 01:06:32.510
impactful studies in patients with PH positive ALL.

1135
01:06:33.130 --> 01:06:37.030
Again, knowing that the burden of cure in our patients is very high due

1136
01:06:37.050 --> 01:06:38.960
to chemotherapy-associated toxicity.

1137
01:06:39.570 --> 01:06:42.910
And in this international collaborative study through our children's oncology group

1138
01:06:42.950 --> 01:06:46.870
and the SVAL consortium in Europe, we also were looking at the potential to

1139
01:06:46.910 --> 01:06:50.790
de-intensify chemotherapy and preserve good outcomes for children with PH

1140
01:06:50.830 --> 01:06:54.810
positive ALL, perhaps even paradoxically improving their outcomes due to a

1141
01:06:54.820 --> 01:06:58.770
reduction in toxic mortality. So patients with PH positive ALL were

1142
01:06:58.830 --> 01:07:02.139
all treated with imatinib at this time because this was universally available

1143
01:07:02.210 --> 01:07:06.190
across the continents, and then patients were randomized to the intensive SVAL

1144
01:07:06.200 --> 01:07:09.999
chemotherapy that was standard of care versus a slightly less intensive but

1145
01:07:10.310 --> 01:07:13.100
COG high-risk B-ALL backbone in the experimental

1146
01:07:13.250 --> 01:07:16.910
arm. Importantly, we amended this study a couple of years ago to

1147
01:07:16.950 --> 01:07:20.510
include patients with ABL class fusions within PH-like ALL, given that

1148
01:07:20.530 --> 01:07:23.830
phenocopying of PH positive biology, and we

1149
01:07:24.370 --> 01:07:27.710
completed accrual to this study just a little bit early, about a year and a half

1150
01:07:27.750 --> 01:07:31.440
ago, with the advent of some of the remarkable data coming out from our

1151
01:07:31.530 --> 01:07:35.330
frontline blinatumomab trials that has really revolutionized, I think, our care of

1152
01:07:35.370 --> 01:07:37.550
children with ALL, and we'll touch on that in a moment.

1153
01:07:38.010 --> 01:07:41.890
But we look forward to hearing outcomes of this trial in the coming years.

1154
01:07:43.050 --> 01:07:46.640
So I think a major question for us in ALL now that we have made such remarkable

1155
01:07:46.690 --> 01:07:50.470
advances in curing children, especially in the era of blinatumomab, is, is there

1156
01:07:50.590 --> 01:07:54.530
still an appetite for targeted inhibitors, or is immunotherapy sufficient, and we

1157
01:07:54.570 --> 01:07:57.950
all should all go home? We certainly know that CD19 and

1158
01:07:57.990 --> 01:08:01.640
CD22 targeted immunotherapies, both antibody-based and cellular,

1159
01:08:02.110 --> 01:08:05.750
have been remarkable in inducing remissions in children with relapsed high-risk

1160
01:08:05.810 --> 01:08:09.010
ALL, where remission was initially not

1161
01:08:09.050 --> 01:08:12.470
possible. But despite this efficacy, we also know that these

1162
01:08:12.530 --> 01:08:15.930
immunotherapies have unique toxicities, and these are not always benign,

1163
01:08:15.990 --> 01:08:18.771
particularly in the cellular immunotherapy space.

1164
01:08:18.830 --> 01:08:22.190
We don't yet know great biomarkers of treatment success or failure, and it's very

1165
01:08:22.210 --> 01:08:25.830
hard to predict this a priori. We also know, especially in the CAR

1166
01:08:25.910 --> 01:08:29.630
T-cell space, that many patients have unfortunately developed very

1167
01:08:29.750 --> 01:08:33.110
fatal mechanisms of immunotherapeutic resistance, and this has been very

1168
01:08:33.170 --> 01:08:36.840
challenging to overcome. And finally, I think as a moment of equity,

1169
01:08:37.150 --> 01:08:41.030
we know that CAR T-cells, in particular, are incredibly expensive and really

1170
01:08:41.110 --> 01:08:43.690
have inequitable access across the world.

1171
01:08:43.710 --> 01:08:46.590
And so it's very difficult to scale this up for most patients.

1172
01:08:47.990 --> 01:08:51.300
And so as I mentioned before, we've been very fortunate, both in adult and

1173
01:08:51.370 --> 01:08:55.271
pediatric ALL, to realize the remarkable benefit of blinatumomab, really

1174
01:08:55.280 --> 01:08:58.960
across the age spectrum. Certainly, our initial trials conducted more than

1175
01:08:58.971 --> 01:09:02.311
15 years ago of CD19 and CD22 targeted antibody

1176
01:09:02.351 --> 01:09:06.271
immunotherapeutics really changed the stage for our patients in relapse.

1177
01:09:06.280 --> 01:09:09.830
And we were very excited in recent trials to be able to move this toward frontline

1178
01:09:09.870 --> 01:09:13.460
investigation with a goal of improving relapse-free survival and

1179
01:09:13.471 --> 01:09:17.370
potentially reducing toxicity. We now know that the superiority of

1180
01:09:17.410 --> 01:09:21.050
blinatumomab compared to conventional chemotherapy is really superior

1181
01:09:21.150 --> 01:09:25.130
across the age spectrum. We saw very remarkable results with more than

1182
01:09:25.170 --> 01:09:28.931
80% long-term disease-free survival in a pilot study conducted in

1183
01:09:28.971 --> 01:09:32.851
Europe by our colleagues in the INTERFONT Consortium for babies with KMT2A

1184
01:09:32.931 --> 01:09:36.580
rearranged ALL treated with a single cycle of consolidated blinatumomab,

1185
01:09:36.931 --> 01:09:39.230
and these data have held out now for more than four years.

1186
01:09:39.950 --> 01:09:43.471
We also were really excited to see the remarkable outcomes of the AALL

1187
01:09:43.490 --> 01:09:47.190
1731 study in which children with standard risk ALL were randomized to

1188
01:09:47.210 --> 01:09:50.790
blinatumomab-based chemoimmunotherapy versus standard of care chemotherapy

1189
01:09:50.830 --> 01:09:54.570
alone. This result was so remarkable that it shut down all of our clinical trials,

1190
01:09:54.600 --> 01:09:57.290
and that was a great thing for our patients, although a very difficult thing for us

1191
01:09:57.350 --> 01:10:01.070
as clinical investigators. And we also have been pleased to learn very much from

1192
01:10:01.110 --> 01:10:04.970
our medical hematology colleagues about the therapeutic potential of blinatumomab

1193
01:10:04.990 --> 01:10:08.800
also for adults with ALL being far superior to conventional chemotherapy.

1194
01:10:09.300 --> 01:10:12.260
And importantly, our adult colleagues have taught us a lot about the potential for

1195
01:10:12.390 --> 01:10:16.020
cure, even with remarkable chemotherapy de-intensification,

1196
01:10:16.350 --> 01:10:19.290
which I think remains a major mission for us now in pediatric ALL.

1197
01:10:20.170 --> 01:10:23.410
And then finally, I think based on the heels of the success of blinatumomab-based

1198
01:10:23.430 --> 01:10:26.870
therapies for patients without PH positive ALL,

1199
01:10:27.370 --> 01:10:30.730
we also have learned a lot from our adult colleagues in Europe and in the US in

1200
01:10:30.790 --> 01:10:34.770
small trials that have also successfully credentialed the addition of TKIs

1201
01:10:34.830 --> 01:10:38.550
to blinatumomab-based therapies, specifically for patients with PH positive

1202
01:10:38.610 --> 01:10:42.530
ALL. And this is a strategy in which we're quite interested in bringing forward to

1203
01:10:42.630 --> 01:10:43.949
pediatric patients as well.

1204
01:10:44.980 --> 01:10:48.470
And so to that end, our successor AALL 2131, or SVAL

1205
01:10:48.610 --> 01:10:51.910
2022 study, is really trying to credential a reduced

1206
01:10:51.970 --> 01:10:55.470
intensity chemotherapy backbone with early intercalation of

1207
01:10:55.490 --> 01:10:58.910
blinatumomab for patients with PH positive as well as ABL class

1208
01:10:58.990 --> 01:11:02.870
PH-like ALL. Importantly, based on very robust preclinical

1209
01:11:02.910 --> 01:11:06.050
data that emerged from Monique Den Boer's laboratory in the Netherlands and my

1210
01:11:06.090 --> 01:11:09.990
laboratory in Philadelphia, we've also realized that one size does not fit all

1211
01:11:10.030 --> 01:11:13.170
in terms of TKI selection for patients with PH-like ALL.

1212
01:11:13.690 --> 01:11:17.130
And so in this trial, patients with PDGFR beta fusions are

1213
01:11:17.170 --> 01:11:21.030
non-randomly assigned to receive imatinib, whereas patients with the other ABL

1214
01:11:21.090 --> 01:11:24.540
class fusions and PH positive ALL are non-randomly assigned to receive

1215
01:11:24.550 --> 01:11:28.460
dasatinib and then go on to receive early application of blinatumomab and

1216
01:11:28.510 --> 01:11:30.050
reduced intensity chemotherapy.

1217
01:11:30.630 --> 01:11:34.270
We hope in this trial to credential a reduced intensity chemotherapy backbone that

1218
01:11:34.290 --> 01:11:37.930
will nonetheless be curative and less toxic, and try also to understand the

1219
01:11:37.950 --> 01:11:41.900
therapeutic potential of this fusion-specific TKI based on very good

1220
01:11:41.950 --> 01:11:42.969
preclinical biology.

1221
01:11:44.630 --> 01:11:48.030
And now I'm going to turn our attention to my other love, acute myeloid leukemia,

1222
01:11:48.130 --> 01:11:51.910
or AML. As you can see here in these survival curves, we've also made

1223
01:11:52.210 --> 01:11:55.640
fairly good progress over the last 40 to 50 years in improving survival for

1224
01:11:55.710 --> 01:11:57.790
patients with AML in the pediatric domain.

1225
01:11:58.290 --> 01:12:01.970
This has largely been due to recognition of appropriate therapy intensification

1226
01:12:02.330 --> 01:12:05.610
and also very broad application of allogeneic hematopoietic stem cell

1227
01:12:05.650 --> 01:12:09.290
transplantation in first remission for patients with highest risk disease,

1228
01:12:09.550 --> 01:12:12.500
either based on genetics or end of induction MRD positivity

1229
01:12:12.610 --> 01:12:16.530
again. However, for pediatric patients with AML, we know that cure comes with

1230
01:12:16.550 --> 01:12:20.270
great cost, particularly with acute and long-term toxicities in the cardiac and

1231
01:12:20.330 --> 01:12:23.900
infectious domains. And unfortunately, in recent years, most of the

1232
01:12:23.930 --> 01:12:27.350
improvements that we've actually made in survival for children with AML have been

1233
01:12:27.410 --> 01:12:31.010
due to improved supportive care and not because we have new drugs, with the

1234
01:12:31.050 --> 01:12:34.958
exception of the CD33 antibody drug conjugate gemtuzumab.For which

1235
01:12:34.978 --> 01:12:38.858
we have demonstrated improvements in disease-free survival in specific subsets of

1236
01:12:38.898 --> 01:12:42.638
patients, particularly KMT2A rearranged AML through recent

1237
01:12:42.678 --> 01:12:44.658
COG and MYCHILD studies in the UK.

1238
01:12:50.218 --> 01:12:53.238
We also know through collaborative team science the incredible genomic

1239
01:12:53.278 --> 01:12:57.258
heterogeneity of AML, and I will say that precision medicine is really important

1240
01:12:57.268 --> 01:13:00.298
to us given these potentially targetable alterations.

1241
01:13:00.738 --> 01:13:03.978
As I mentioned before, we are taking a lot of children to transplant in first

1242
01:13:04.038 --> 01:13:07.228
remission because we know that chemotherapy alone does not cure them.

1243
01:13:07.237 --> 01:13:11.118
Although I will say for specific high-risk biologic subtypes of AML, we

1244
01:13:11.178 --> 01:13:14.548
don't always know that early transplant actually improves overall survival for

1245
01:13:14.578 --> 01:13:18.478
these patients. And if we can possibly find an Achilles heel within these leukemias

1246
01:13:18.638 --> 01:13:21.878
that may be immunable to targeted therapies, we really would like to credential

1247
01:13:21.918 --> 01:13:23.698
those approaches and bring them to the frontline.

1248
01:13:25.278 --> 01:13:28.878
We know that chemotherapy resistance is a huge contributor to subsequent

1249
01:13:28.958 --> 01:13:32.348
relapse. And for children who relapse with AML early within a year of

1250
01:13:32.398 --> 01:13:36.198
diagnosis or for any child who relapses after transplant, the

1251
01:13:36.238 --> 01:13:39.357
survival historically with salvage chemotherapies is less than 10%.

1252
01:13:39.497 --> 01:13:43.458
So we simply need to do better. And we have been very pleased, I think, to benefit

1253
01:13:43.478 --> 01:13:46.978
from all of the remarkable knowledge gained by our medical hematology colleagues in

1254
01:13:46.998 --> 01:13:50.518
early phase clinical trials now credentialing a lot of targeted therapies.

1255
01:13:50.858 --> 01:13:54.838
And we are very hopeful to be able to get these also to pediatric investigation

1256
01:13:55.078 --> 01:13:58.718
to be able to credential the right doses and then be able to bring these therapies

1257
01:13:58.758 --> 01:14:00.978
forward to the frontline to try to prevent relapse.

1258
01:14:01.578 --> 01:14:04.918
And I will make a note that I think that precision medicine for us in pediatric AML

1259
01:14:04.978 --> 01:14:08.238
is particularly important. We have not appreciated the successes of

1260
01:14:08.278 --> 01:14:11.778
immunotherapies nearly as greatly for pediatric AML as we have in

1261
01:14:11.838 --> 01:14:15.598
B-ALL. And so I think that this is really an effort where we need to double down on

1262
01:14:15.608 --> 01:14:16.438
precision medicine.

1263
01:14:17.698 --> 01:14:21.298
And some of the very successful examples of this for us in pediatric AML, I think

1264
01:14:21.318 --> 01:14:24.628
borrowing a page from our adult colleagues certainly have been with the addition of

1265
01:14:24.638 --> 01:14:28.218
FLT3 inhibitors to chemotherapy for patients with FLT3 mutant AML.

1266
01:14:28.758 --> 01:14:31.878
We've known for a long time that these are some of our highest-risk patients, and

1267
01:14:31.938 --> 01:14:35.078
we always have taken the majority of these patients to hematopoietic stem cell

1268
01:14:35.138 --> 01:14:39.038
transplantation. Knowing that patients in the adult space could

1269
01:14:39.078 --> 01:14:42.878
benefit appreciably from FLT3 inhibitors initially given as monotherapy in

1270
01:14:42.898 --> 01:14:46.598
relapse and then ultimately credentialed in combination with frontline therapies

1271
01:14:46.618 --> 01:14:50.238
for patients with newly diagnosed disease, this has really been a game changer.

1272
01:14:50.598 --> 01:14:54.058
And we've also, through our Children's Oncology Group AML 1031 study,

1273
01:14:54.458 --> 01:14:58.278
demonstrated the significant benefit of serafinib addition early in

1274
01:14:58.318 --> 01:15:02.208
chemotherapy to patients with FLT3-ITD AML and including

1275
01:15:02.238 --> 01:15:05.518
post-transplant maintenance options when available.

1276
01:15:05.558 --> 01:15:08.898
However, these trials have also taught us a lot about the impact of co-mutations in

1277
01:15:08.938 --> 01:15:12.918
FLT3 mutant AML, and we certainly know that patients with co-occurring NPM198

1278
01:15:13.038 --> 01:15:16.658
NSD fusions remain very difficult to treat and do not necessarily

1279
01:15:16.698 --> 01:15:20.538
benefit from FLT3 inhibitor addition to chemotherapy for reasons we don't fully yet

1280
01:15:20.558 --> 01:15:24.198
understand. And despite the FDA approval now of four FLT3

1281
01:15:24.238 --> 01:15:28.138
inhibitors for adults with AML, none of these inhibitors are currently

1282
01:15:28.158 --> 01:15:31.498
approved for children. So we really need to do better despite the great data that

1283
01:15:31.538 --> 01:15:32.218
we already have.

1284
01:15:33.578 --> 01:15:37.118
We also have been very jealous of our adult colleagues with the remarkable success

1285
01:15:37.158 --> 01:15:40.747
of BCL-2 inhibition, particularly with venetoclax-based therapies.

1286
01:15:40.778 --> 01:15:44.598
This is a high priority for us in pediatric leukemias, but unfortunately, we

1287
01:15:44.658 --> 01:15:46.638
have quite limited access and no approval.

1288
01:15:47.278 --> 01:15:50.918
We know through adult trials that venetoclax addition to

1289
01:15:50.978 --> 01:15:54.878
intensive and non-intensive chemotherapy has been a home run, and we are very

1290
01:15:54.958 --> 01:15:57.898
hopeful to be able to credential this also for pediatric patients.

1291
01:15:58.378 --> 01:16:01.938
We have been able to conduct some small relapse studies in AML as well as some

1292
01:16:01.978 --> 01:16:05.758
frontline studies recently in ALL looking at venetoclax addition to

1293
01:16:05.778 --> 01:16:09.678
standard of care chemotherapy. And in anecdotal real-world studies, we've

1294
01:16:09.738 --> 01:16:12.978
also shown that this can be remarkably effective even in patients with multiple

1295
01:16:13.018 --> 01:16:15.758
relapse. And so we are very eager to bring this forward.

1296
01:16:16.578 --> 01:16:20.378
In our current Blood Cancer United sponsored APAL 2020D study, we are

1297
01:16:20.458 --> 01:16:24.398
randomizing for children with first relapse of AML to understand

1298
01:16:24.438 --> 01:16:28.058
the therapeutic potential of venetoclax addition to fludarabine, cytarabine, and

1299
01:16:28.098 --> 01:16:31.958
gemtuzumab chemotherapy and trying to understand at a registration level

1300
01:16:32.258 --> 01:16:35.118
if this can improve outcomes and potentially lead to approval for us.

1301
01:16:35.698 --> 01:16:38.998
And I will also note that there are other BCL-2 inhibitors out there, and we remain

1302
01:16:39.018 --> 01:16:42.758
very eager to have conversations with such companies to be able to

1303
01:16:42.798 --> 01:16:46.278
explore these in the pediatric setting as well.

1304
01:16:46.298 --> 01:16:49.958
And then finally, I think we've been really excited by the remarkable data coming

1305
01:16:50.018 --> 01:16:53.957
out with menin inhibitors in the past couple of years, primarily in adult

1306
01:16:54.018 --> 01:16:56.978
AML studies. But we have been fortunate to either include

1307
01:16:57.018 --> 01:17:00.798
pediatric patients with some of the biologic relevant

1308
01:17:00.878 --> 01:17:03.898
subtypes of leukemias in these trials or to conduct

1309
01:17:03.908 --> 01:17:06.718
pediatric-specific investigations alone.

1310
01:17:06.778 --> 01:17:10.598
We now know that the now FDA-approved menin inhibitor, revumenib,

1311
01:17:10.978 --> 01:17:14.558
has demonstrated remarkable activity when given as monotherapy with 20% to

1312
01:17:14.738 --> 01:17:18.458
30% complete remission rates in patients with relapsed acute

1313
01:17:18.498 --> 01:17:22.338
leukemias harboring KMT2A rearrangements, NPM198 rearrangements, or

1314
01:17:22.398 --> 01:17:26.378
NPM1 mutant acute leukemias. These remission rates are even better when we

1315
01:17:26.398 --> 01:17:29.818
combine it with chemotherapy, with about 50% of relapse patients going into

1316
01:17:29.838 --> 01:17:33.248
remission again. And I think we've been very excited to hear at ASH and other

1317
01:17:33.318 --> 01:17:36.538
meetings the remarkable frontline data now emerging from adults with these

1318
01:17:36.578 --> 01:17:40.078
leukemias with 80% to 100% complete remission rates and long-term

1319
01:17:40.158 --> 01:17:43.418
survival. We are also now studying this in our COG

1320
01:17:43.778 --> 01:17:47.538
AALL 2121 study in infants with

1321
01:17:48.118 --> 01:17:51.978
relapsed ALL harboring KMT2A rearrangements, and we also are

1322
01:17:52.018 --> 01:17:54.398
doing this in other pediatric institutional studies.

1323
01:17:55.118 --> 01:17:58.578
We've also been pleased through the Blood Cancer United consortium in our APAL 2020

1324
01:17:58.598 --> 01:18:02.218
case study to look at the menin inhibitor ziftamenib in combination with intensive

1325
01:18:02.278 --> 01:18:06.018
chemotherapy also for children, specifically with relapsed acute leukemias

1326
01:18:06.058 --> 01:18:09.998
harboring those genetic alterations and have accrued robustly to this trial.

1327
01:18:10.818 --> 01:18:14.398
There are, of course, other very exciting menin inhibitors out there with very nice

1328
01:18:14.478 --> 01:18:18.378
adult data, and we are in conversations for pediatric-specific investigation

1329
01:18:18.447 --> 01:18:19.868
with many of these companies as well.

1330
01:18:20.658 --> 01:18:24.078
And finally, of course, our goal of all of this work is to bring menin inhibitors

1331
01:18:24.118 --> 01:18:27.678
to the frontline to be able to decrease the relapse risk for these highest-risk

1332
01:18:27.718 --> 01:18:31.626
patients.And finally, in the last couple of minutes, I just want

1333
01:18:31.646 --> 01:18:33.826
to touch on a couple of near and dear things to our hearts.

1334
01:18:34.066 --> 01:18:37.466
We certainly know that there are some very rare pediatric myeloid leukemias that

1335
01:18:37.486 --> 01:18:41.166
may be particularly amenable to precision medicine therapies, including

1336
01:18:41.206 --> 01:18:44.636
chronic myeloid leukemia or CML. We know that this is not

1337
01:18:44.646 --> 01:18:48.606
necessarily the public health menace of pediatric oncology, but this remains a

1338
01:18:48.646 --> 01:18:51.886
very important disease given the chronicity of this leukemia and the need for

1339
01:18:51.946 --> 01:18:55.526
long-term treatment. We know that the biology of pediatric CML is

1340
01:18:55.546 --> 01:18:59.476
potentially more aggressive than that in adults, and we also know that cure comes

1341
01:18:59.486 --> 01:19:03.406
with greater cost, potentially, given the endocrinopathies that ensue

1342
01:19:03.446 --> 01:19:06.846
from patients receiving chronic TKIs in the developing children space.

1343
01:19:07.626 --> 01:19:10.846
We know that most children, fortunately, can achieve deeper mission with chronic

1344
01:19:10.906 --> 01:19:14.646
daily TKI monotherapy, but adherence is extremely important

1345
01:19:14.886 --> 01:19:16.406
to maintaining these deeper missions.

1346
01:19:16.936 --> 01:19:20.716
We also know that there are unique toxicities of TKI therapy, and

1347
01:19:20.766 --> 01:19:24.586
over time, with chronic exposure, the ABL1 resistance mutations

1348
01:19:24.646 --> 01:19:28.246
can develop. And again, given the potential for decreased linear growth

1349
01:19:28.326 --> 01:19:31.686
potential, children with CML who are on chronic TKI

1350
01:19:31.706 --> 01:19:35.536
monotherapy require a lot of endocrinology collaboration, potentially for

1351
01:19:35.546 --> 01:19:38.706
growth hormone supplementation, management of thyroid issues.

1352
01:19:39.056 --> 01:19:42.966
And we are very hopeful that potentially other TKIs such as Bosutinib may have

1353
01:19:43.006 --> 01:19:46.566
fewer effects in this domain, but still need to be studied with longer-term

1354
01:19:46.576 --> 01:19:50.186
follow-up. And then finally, even though there have been remarkable results

1355
01:19:50.286 --> 01:19:54.086
in adults with CML or PH-positive ALL with third generation and some of the

1356
01:19:54.146 --> 01:19:57.996
other next-generation TKIs, our access to these important inhibitors in

1357
01:19:58.046 --> 01:20:01.586
pediatrics has been extremely limited through early phase clinical trials or not

1358
01:20:01.626 --> 01:20:05.596
available to us at all. And then finally, we really need to understand in this

1359
01:20:05.626 --> 01:20:09.006
rare patient population which children can be cured and potentially stop

1360
01:20:09.046 --> 01:20:13.026
TKIs. We know some data from adults that patients can successfully

1361
01:20:13.066 --> 01:20:16.926
stop TKIs temporarily or potentially even permanently, and

1362
01:20:16.986 --> 01:20:20.696
ongoing work through our COG AALL18P1 study is helping us to

1363
01:20:20.746 --> 01:20:23.866
understand that question a little bit better, specifically in pediatrics.

1364
01:20:26.306 --> 01:20:29.876
And then finally, I think near and dear to all of our hearts as clinicians is also

1365
01:20:29.906 --> 01:20:33.526
juvenile myelomonocytic leukemia or JMML, a one in a million

1366
01:20:33.566 --> 01:20:37.226
diagnosis that I like to call the ultimate RASopathy, given the

1367
01:20:37.286 --> 01:20:41.066
clear genetic drivers in RAS pathway mutations.

1368
01:20:41.086 --> 01:20:43.606
We know historically that these are very chemotherapy-resistant

1369
01:20:45.086 --> 01:20:48.946
leukemias, in which patients receive some chemotherapy

1370
01:20:49.006 --> 01:20:52.766
reduction really to maximize the success of allogeneic stem cell transplant.

1371
01:20:53.166 --> 01:20:56.606
But historically, approximately 50% of children still went on to relapse.

1372
01:20:57.466 --> 01:21:00.926
Very robust preclinical studies that have been led through collaborative work in

1373
01:21:00.966 --> 01:21:04.866
the United States and in Europe have identified the therapeutic potential of

1374
01:21:04.906 --> 01:21:08.756
targeting a lot of these mutations and aberrant signaling pathways

1375
01:21:08.886 --> 01:21:10.686
with various targeted inhibitors.

1376
01:21:10.726 --> 01:21:14.286
Of course, MEK inhibitors being, I think, the most important, given these RAS

1377
01:21:14.306 --> 01:21:18.036
pathway alterations. And based on recent successes in the

1378
01:21:18.106 --> 01:21:22.026
relapse space, looking at the MEK inhibitor trametinib as monotherapy in

1379
01:21:22.066 --> 01:21:25.495
children with relapsed JMML inducing about 50% remission rates,

1380
01:21:26.086 --> 01:21:29.495
we are very pleased now to be conducting the international TACKLE consortium

1381
01:21:29.806 --> 01:21:33.706
2020-004 study that is looking at trametinib for children with JMML

1382
01:21:33.746 --> 01:21:37.726
with risk-adapted chemotherapy based on their mutation status as well as

1383
01:21:37.806 --> 01:21:38.926
methylation profiles.

1384
01:21:40.206 --> 01:21:43.626
So I hope that I have shown you today that we still have a lot of work and a lot of

1385
01:21:43.666 --> 01:21:47.106
interest in precision medicine in high-risk leukemias, and I will leave you here

1386
01:21:47.146 --> 01:21:51.046
with these major questions. For our patients with ALL, of course, the

1387
01:21:51.126 --> 01:21:53.226
who, what, where, when, why of immunotherapies.

1388
01:21:53.786 --> 01:21:57.186
But yet I will still argue to you that there is an important role of precision

1389
01:21:57.226 --> 01:22:00.846
medicine therapies and perhaps combination with immunotherapies to be able to

1390
01:22:00.886 --> 01:22:04.726
further reduce chemotherapy intensity and improve cure rates with less toxicity.

1391
01:22:05.646 --> 01:22:08.826
AML remains a major problem for us and I think is ripe for precision medicine

1392
01:22:08.886 --> 01:22:11.046
opportunities given the genomic landscape.

1393
01:22:11.495 --> 01:22:15.126
And then finally, for these rare pediatric leukemias, it's very difficult for us to

1394
01:22:15.166 --> 01:22:17.846
run clinical trials, especially randomized ones.

1395
01:22:17.886 --> 01:22:21.366
So how do we ask the right question, potentially once a decade, or how do we learn

1396
01:22:21.406 --> 01:22:22.826
a little bit more from real-world data?

1397
01:22:23.526 --> 01:22:26.026
And with that, I'll thank you for your attention and glad to take questions.

1398
01:22:34.986 --> 01:22:37.166
Camille Choquette from Institute for

1399
01:22:38.586 --> 01:22:41.506
Research in Cancer and Immunology, Montreal, Canada.

1400
01:22:42.346 --> 01:22:46.066
Thanks for your talk. I was wondering if you, given the great

1401
01:22:46.146 --> 01:22:50.026
results you got combining menin inhibitor in AML

1402
01:22:50.266 --> 01:22:53.386
and chemotherapy, I was wondering if you thought of

1403
01:22:53.426 --> 01:22:56.826
investigating the use of menin inhibitor with venetoclax, for

1404
01:22:56.866 --> 01:22:57.565
example.

1405
01:22:58.686 --> 01:23:00.006
No, thanks for that great question.

1406
01:23:00.486 --> 01:23:04.206
We are very intrigued by the therapeutic potential of venetoclax,

1407
01:23:04.366 --> 01:23:07.046
particularly in combination with hypomethylating agents.

1408
01:23:07.286 --> 01:23:10.946
I think azacitidine and venetoclax have been very important

1409
01:23:11.206 --> 01:23:14.855
kind of real-world therapies for most of us with relapsed

1410
01:23:14.946 --> 01:23:18.746
AML patients. This is not FDA approved, so we haven't been able to

1411
01:23:18.906 --> 01:23:21.186
conduct a lot of clinical trials in this domain.

1412
01:23:21.706 --> 01:23:25.626
But we're very intrigued, especially by now the adult frontline AML studies

1413
01:23:25.666 --> 01:23:28.806
that are looking at combinations of hypomethylators with venetoclax and menin

1414
01:23:28.866 --> 01:23:32.826
inhibitors. We can anecdotally say in pediatrics this is extremely

1415
01:23:32.906 --> 01:23:36.646
well clinically tolerated and we think has high potential to be quite

1416
01:23:36.686 --> 01:23:40.286
efficacious. And we would love to be able to study that question more formally in

1417
01:23:40.326 --> 01:23:41.066
clinical trials.

1418
01:23:41.746 --> 01:23:42.206
Thank you.

1419
01:23:46.026 --> 01:23:49.506
Hi. Giselle from Scott Durum's lab,

1420
01:23:49.606 --> 01:23:50.166
NCI.

1421
01:23:51.106 --> 01:23:53.526
It's always very nice to hear your talk.

1422
01:23:53.666 --> 01:23:56.086
You know I'm a very big fan of your work.

1423
01:23:56.846 --> 01:23:59.596
I have two questions for you. One is,

1424
01:24:00.466 --> 01:24:03.516
from a translational perspective, what

1425
01:24:04.306 --> 01:24:07.806
do you think it's currently missing in our preclinical

1426
01:24:07.886 --> 01:24:10.566
models or our functional validation

1427
01:24:10.666 --> 01:24:14.346
pipelines that slows the

1428
01:24:14.416 --> 01:24:14.806
move

1429
01:24:15.686 --> 01:24:17.806
from the genomic discovery? We have a

1430
01:24:18.746 --> 01:24:22.106
considering amount of genomic data now available

1431
01:24:23.246 --> 01:24:26.806
to identify really real drivers

1432
01:24:27.726 --> 01:24:31.706
in clinically relevant targets. And the second one

1433
01:24:31.786 --> 01:24:34.456
is if you could talk a little bit about

1434
01:24:34.666 --> 01:24:38.504
your... opinion regarding

1435
01:24:38.504 --> 01:24:42.014
the post immunotherapy lineage switch

1436
01:24:43.134 --> 01:24:46.694
that's coming up a lot in recent research.

1437
01:24:46.734 --> 01:24:47.394
Thank you.

1438
01:24:47.454 --> 01:24:49.514
Yeah. Thanks for those great questions.

1439
01:24:49.854 --> 01:24:52.994
I actually think that in the preclinical space, we're doing pretty well.

1440
01:24:53.294 --> 01:24:56.414
I think that we've been very lucky both preclinically and now

1441
01:24:56.454 --> 01:24:59.924
clinically, to have very robust genomic definition

1442
01:25:00.014 --> 01:25:03.404
pipelines. So I think we're actually doing quite well in identifying our patients.

1443
01:25:04.134 --> 01:25:07.994
And even in the laboratory space, trying to match those mutations with the right

1444
01:25:08.034 --> 01:25:11.974
medicines. I think we've been very lucky in the pediatric space to have

1445
01:25:11.994 --> 01:25:14.974
relatively good models with patient-derived xenograft models.

1446
01:25:15.634 --> 01:25:18.934
I will say that we are extraordinarily grateful to our patients and families who

1447
01:25:18.974 --> 01:25:22.384
biobank on our clinical trials. We literally couldn't do this work without

1448
01:25:22.434 --> 01:25:26.184
them. So I think that we've actually done a fairly good job trying to

1449
01:25:26.194 --> 01:25:29.774
identify relevant inhibitors or even chemotherapies that may have

1450
01:25:30.134 --> 01:25:33.474
particular sensitivity against specific genetic subtypes.

1451
01:25:34.774 --> 01:25:36.894
We know that our models are, of course, not fully predictive.

1452
01:25:37.254 --> 01:25:40.574
Our patient-derived mouse models are immunocompromised.

1453
01:25:40.774 --> 01:25:44.674
They don't fully recapitulate the microenvironmental factors that we know may

1454
01:25:44.714 --> 01:25:47.754
contribute to therapy resistance, particularly in myeloid leukemias.

1455
01:25:48.494 --> 01:25:50.714
But I think we've actually done pretty well in that space.

1456
01:25:51.254 --> 01:25:53.494
For me, the big gap is honestly drug access.

1457
01:25:54.114 --> 01:25:57.454
As somebody who works in the laboratory but also works very much in the early phase

1458
01:25:57.514 --> 01:26:01.254
clinical trial space, being able to access the right drugs

1459
01:26:01.774 --> 01:26:05.134
before we have to wait for mature Phase III frontline clinical trial data from

1460
01:26:05.174 --> 01:26:08.934
adults is really challenging. But we also do a lot of these Phase I

1461
01:26:08.944 --> 01:26:12.514
clinical trials at risk, where we want to get in early enough where we're able to

1462
01:26:12.524 --> 01:26:16.354
access those inhibitors. But I think unfortunately, as many of the clinicians in

1463
01:26:16.394 --> 01:26:20.074
this audience knows, sometimes our trials go belly up at the 11th hour

1464
01:26:20.154 --> 01:26:24.134
because of negative adult trial data, even if we have a clear biologic

1465
01:26:24.174 --> 01:26:28.014
signal. So I think it's tricky, but I think that there's a small

1466
01:26:28.054 --> 01:26:31.994
but mighty denominator here who really will continue to push that

1467
01:26:32.034 --> 01:26:34.874
translational impact from the labs to the clinic.

1468
01:26:36.014 --> 01:26:39.594
And then to answer your second question, we're very interested in lineage switch.

1469
01:26:39.674 --> 01:26:43.634
I think many of us, especially in the KMT2A rearranged

1470
01:26:43.674 --> 01:26:47.354
ALL space, have realized because these are plastic and stemmy

1471
01:26:47.374 --> 01:26:51.114
leukemias, they of course can morph with lineage drift or

1472
01:26:51.154 --> 01:26:55.134
switch into myeloid phenotypes biologically, even sometimes rarely

1473
01:26:55.174 --> 01:26:57.134
with chemotherapy or with blinatumomab.

1474
01:26:57.914 --> 01:27:01.824
Certainly in this era of CD19 CAR T-cells that are very persistent, where

1475
01:27:01.834 --> 01:27:05.554
we think that they're really putting a sledgehammer of antigenic pressure.

1476
01:27:05.774 --> 01:27:08.754
That is really where we have seen, I think, the most lineage switch.

1477
01:27:09.754 --> 01:27:12.504
I don't know about any of the clinicians in the audience, but every single one of

1478
01:27:12.534 --> 01:27:15.814
my patients who has developed AML lineage switch, we have not been able to save.

1479
01:27:15.874 --> 01:27:17.834
So I think that this is a really important problem.

1480
01:27:18.574 --> 01:27:22.244
We are very hopeful that menin inhibitors, because they are attacking the insides

1481
01:27:22.294 --> 01:27:25.634
of the leukemias and those critical drivers, may be a little bit more

1482
01:27:25.674 --> 01:27:29.474
immunophenotype agnostic in these very stemmy plastic leukemias.

1483
01:27:29.484 --> 01:27:33.463
And so we wonder if menin inhibitors can go a long way into helping

1484
01:27:33.474 --> 01:27:37.274
prevent lineage switch. There's other preclinical work ongoing

1485
01:27:37.334 --> 01:27:41.234
looking at other antigenic targets, specifically in KMT2A rearranged ALL,

1486
01:27:41.294 --> 01:27:45.214
like FLT3, where we've also seen, at least preclinically, good

1487
01:27:45.234 --> 01:27:48.694
therapeutic potential against both ALL and AML phenotypes, so.

1488
01:27:49.494 --> 01:27:52.574
But I think we need to give non-cross-reactive therapy and probably best

1489
01:27:52.634 --> 01:27:56.463
combination therapy. And I would love to understand if menin inhibitors and

1490
01:27:56.514 --> 01:27:59.774
immunotherapies could help reduce that risk. That's a great question. Thanks.

1491
01:28:01.414 --> 01:28:05.274
Good. I think we're out of time today, so I wanted to

1492
01:28:05.314 --> 01:28:08.784
thank Dr. Ziegler and Dr. Janeway for their outstanding talks.

1493
01:28:08.874 --> 01:28:11.774
I really thank all of you for your attention and being here, and I hope you have a

1494
01:28:11.794 --> 01:28:12.584
great rest of the meeting.
